WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.000 --> 00:00:03.934
[applause]

00:00:16.734 --> 00:00:20.467
Pausch: MAKE ME EARN IT.

00:00:20.467 --> 00:00:21.467
IT'S A--

00:00:21.467 --> 00:00:23.767
man: YOU DID.

00:00:23.767 --> 00:00:26.234
Pausch: IT'S WONDERFUL
TO BE HERE.

00:00:26.234 --> 00:00:28.434
WHAT INDIRA DIDN'T TELL YOU
IS THAT THIS LECTURE SERIES

00:00:28.434 --> 00:00:30.400
USED TO BE CALLED
"THE LAST LECTURE."

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:32.801
IF YOU HAD ONE LAST LECTURE
TO GIVE BEFORE YOU DIED,

00:00:32.801 --> 00:00:34.100
WHAT WOULD IT BE?

00:00:34.100 --> 00:00:35.968
I THOUGHT, "DAMN,
I FINALLY NAILED THE VENUE,

00:00:35.968 --> 00:00:37.801
AND THEY RENAMED IT."

00:00:37.801 --> 00:00:42.133
SO, YOU KNOW, IN CASE THERE'S
ANYBODY WHO WANDERED IN

00:00:42.133 --> 00:00:43.501
AND DOESN'T KNOW
THE BACKSTORY,

00:00:43.501 --> 00:00:44.868
MY DAD ALWAYS TAUGHT ME,

00:00:44.868 --> 00:00:47.000
WHEN THERE'S AN ELEPHANT
IN THE ROOM, INTRODUCE THEM.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:49.434
IF YOU LOOK AT MY CAT SCANS,

00:00:49.434 --> 00:00:51.567
THERE ARE APPROXIMATELY
TEN TUMORS IN MY LIVER,

00:00:51.567 --> 00:00:53.033
AND THE DOCTORS TOLD ME

00:00:53.033 --> 00:00:55.000
THREE TO SIX MONTHS
OF GOOD HEALTH LEFT.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.267
THAT WAS A MONTH AGO,
SO YOU CAN DO THE MATH.

00:00:58.267 --> 00:01:01.667
I HAVE SOME OF THE BEST DOCTORS
IN THE WORLD.

00:01:01.667 --> 00:01:03.100
SO THAT IS WHAT IT IS.

00:01:03.100 --> 00:01:05.200
WE CAN'T CHANGE IT,
AND WE JUST HAVE TO DECIDE

00:01:05.200 --> 00:01:06.601
HOW WE'RE GOING TO RESPOND
TO THAT.

00:01:06.601 --> 00:01:08.434
WE CANNOT CHANGE THE CARDS
WE ARE DEALT,

00:01:08.434 --> 00:01:10.601
JUST HOW WE PLAY THE HAND.

00:01:10.601 --> 00:01:14.434
IF I DON'T SEEM AS DEPRESSED
OR MOROSE AS I SHOULD BE,

00:01:14.434 --> 00:01:15.701
SORRY TO DISAPPOINT YOU.

00:01:15.701 --> 00:01:18.467
[laughter]

00:01:18.467 --> 00:01:20.634
AND I ASSURE YOU,
I AM NOT IN DENIAL.

00:01:20.634 --> 00:01:22.667
IT'S NOT LIKE I'M NOT AWARE
OF WHAT'S GOING ON.

00:01:22.667 --> 00:01:26.033
MY FAMILY, MY THREE KIDS,
MY WIFE, WE JUST DECAMPED.

00:01:26.033 --> 00:01:28.801
WE BOUGHT A LOVELY HOUSE
IN CHESAPEAKE, VIRGINIA,

00:01:28.801 --> 00:01:30.200
NEAR NORFOLK,
AND WE'RE DOING THAT

00:01:30.200 --> 00:01:31.367
BECAUSE THAT'S A BETTER PLACE

00:01:31.367 --> 00:01:33.734
FOR THE FAMILY TO BE,
DOWN THE ROAD.

00:01:33.734 --> 00:01:34.901
AND THE OTHER THING IS

00:01:34.901 --> 00:01:36.667
I AM IN PHENOMENALLY GOOD HEALTH
RIGHT NOW.

00:01:36.667 --> 00:01:37.968
I MEAN, IT'S THE GREATEST THING

00:01:37.968 --> 00:01:40.367
OF COGNITIVE DISSONANCE
YOU WILL EVER SEE

00:01:40.367 --> 00:01:42.934
IS THE FACT THAT I AM
IN REALLY GOOD SHAPE.

00:01:42.934 --> 00:01:47.000
IN FACT, I'M IN BETTER SHAPE
THAN MOST OF YOU.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:01:49.934
[applause]

00:01:58.434 --> 00:02:00.334
SO ANYBODY WHO WANTS TO CRY
OR PITY ME

00:02:00.334 --> 00:02:01.934
CAN COME DOWN
AND DO A FEW OF THOSE,

00:02:01.934 --> 00:02:03.501
AND THEN YOU MAY PITY ME.

00:02:03.501 --> 00:02:05.367
[laughter]

00:02:05.367 --> 00:02:07.400
ALL RIGHT, SO WHAT WE'RE
NOT TALKING ABOUT TODAY,

00:02:07.400 --> 00:02:09.334
WE'RE NOT TALKING ABOUT CANCER,

00:02:09.334 --> 00:02:11.234
BECAUSE I SPENT A LOT OF TIME
TALKING ABOUT THAT,

00:02:11.234 --> 00:02:12.567
AND I'M REALLY NOT INTERESTED.

00:02:12.567 --> 00:02:14.400
IF YOU HAVE ANY HERBAL
SUPPLEMENTS OR REMEDIES,

00:02:14.400 --> 00:02:15.534
PLEASE STAY AWAY FROM ME.

00:02:15.534 --> 00:02:17.067
[laughter]

00:02:17.067 --> 00:02:18.634
AND WE'RE NOT GOING
TO TALK ABOUT THINGS

00:02:18.634 --> 00:02:19.767
THAT ARE EVEN MORE IMPORTANT

00:02:19.767 --> 00:02:21.467
THAN ACHIEVING
YOUR CHILDHOOD DREAMS.

00:02:21.467 --> 00:02:22.934
WE'RE NOT GOING TO TALK
ABOUT MY WIFE.

00:02:22.934 --> 00:02:24.868
WE'RE NOT TALKING ABOUT MY KIDS,
BECAUSE I'M GOOD,

00:02:24.868 --> 00:02:25.968
BUT I'M NOT GOOD ENOUGH

00:02:25.968 --> 00:02:27.501
TO TALK ABOUT THAT
WITHOUT TEARING UP.

00:02:27.501 --> 00:02:29.267
SO WE'RE JUST GOING TO TAKE THAT
OFF THE TABLE.

00:02:29.267 --> 00:02:31.367
THAT'S MUCH MORE IMPORTANT.

00:02:31.367 --> 00:02:34.067
AND WE'RE NOT GOING TO TALK
ABOUT SPIRITUALITY AND RELIGION.

00:02:34.067 --> 00:02:35.968
ALTHOUGH I WILL TELL YOU
THAT I HAVE EXPERIENCED

00:02:35.968 --> 00:02:38.267
A DEATHBED CONVERSION.

00:02:38.267 --> 00:02:39.868
I JUST BOUGHT A MACINTOSH.

00:02:39.868 --> 00:02:42.801
[applause]

00:02:48.901 --> 00:02:53.300
NOW, I KNEW I'D GET 9%
OF THE AUDIENCE WITH THAT.

00:02:53.300 --> 00:02:55.501
ALL RIGHT, SO WHAT IS TODAY'S
TALK ABOUT THEN?

00:02:55.501 --> 00:02:59.534
IT'S ABOUT MY CHILDHOOD DREAMS
AND HOW I HAVE ACHIEVED THEM--

00:02:59.534 --> 00:03:01.434
I'VE BEEN VERY FORTUNATE
THAT WAY--

00:03:01.434 --> 00:03:03.601
HOW I BELIEVE I'VE BEEN ABLE
TO ENABLE THE DREAMS--

00:03:03.601 --> 00:03:06.634
I'VE BEEN ABLE TO ENABLE
THE DREAMS OF OTHERS,

00:03:06.634 --> 00:03:08.834
AND TO SOME DEGREE,
LESSONS LEARNED--

00:03:08.834 --> 00:03:09.968
I'M A PROFESSOR;

00:03:09.968 --> 00:03:12.100
THERE SHOULD BE
SOME LESSONS LEARNED--

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:14.767
AND HOW YOU CAN USE THE STUFF
YOU HEAR TODAY

00:03:14.767 --> 00:03:17.501
TO ACHIEVE YOUR DREAMS
OR ENABLE THE DREAMS OF OTHERS.

00:03:17.501 --> 00:03:19.000
AND AS YOU GET OLDER,
YOU MAY FIND

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:20.701
THAT ENABLING THE DREAMS
OF OTHERS THING

00:03:20.701 --> 00:03:22.901
IS EVEN MORE FUN.

00:03:22.901 --> 00:03:24.834
SO WHAT WERE
MY CHILDHOOD DREAMS?

00:03:24.834 --> 00:03:27.300
WELL, YOU KNOW, I HAD
A REALLY GOOD CHILDHOOD,

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:28.834
I MEAN, NO KIDDING AROUND.

00:03:28.834 --> 00:03:31.234
I WAS GOING BACK THROUGH
THE FAMILY ARCHIVES,

00:03:31.234 --> 00:03:33.067
AND WHAT
WAS REALLY AMAZING WAS,

00:03:33.067 --> 00:03:35.100
I COULDN'T FIND ANY PICTURES
OF ME AS A KID

00:03:35.100 --> 00:03:37.467
WHERE I WASN'T SMILING,
ALL RIGHT?

00:03:37.467 --> 00:03:42.834
AND THAT WAS JUST
A VERY GRATIFYING THING.

00:03:42.834 --> 00:03:45.400
THERE WAS OUR DOG, RIGHT?

00:03:45.400 --> 00:03:47.934
AW, THANK YOU.

00:03:47.934 --> 00:03:50.901
AND THERE I ACTUALLY
HAVE A PICTURE OF ME DREAMING.

00:03:50.901 --> 00:03:53.133
[laughter]

00:03:53.133 --> 00:03:54.534
AND I DID A LOT OF THAT.

00:03:54.534 --> 00:03:58.100
YOU KNOW, THERE WAS A LOT
OF "WAKE UPS," YOU KNOW?

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:01.267
AND IT WAS AN EASY TIME
TO DREAM.

00:04:01.267 --> 00:04:05.100
I WAS BORN IN 1960,
ALL RIGHT?

00:04:05.100 --> 00:04:06.968
WHEN YOU'RE EIGHT
OR NINE YEARS OLD

00:04:06.968 --> 00:04:09.767
AND YOU LOOK AT THE TV SET
AND MEN ARE LANDING ON THE MOON,

00:04:09.767 --> 00:04:11.834
ANYTHING IS POSSIBLE,

00:04:11.834 --> 00:04:15.200
AND THAT'S SOMETHING
WE SHOULD NOT LOSE SIGHT OF,

00:04:15.200 --> 00:04:16.567
IS THAT THE INSPIRATION

00:04:16.567 --> 00:04:20.267
AND THE PERMISSION TO DREAM
IS HUGE.

00:04:20.267 --> 00:04:22.200
SO WHAT WERE
MY CHILDHOOD DREAMS?

00:04:22.200 --> 00:04:24.934
YOU MAY NOT AGREE
WITH THIS LIST, BUT I WAS THERE.

00:04:24.934 --> 00:04:26.734
[laughter]

00:04:26.734 --> 00:04:28.133
BEING IN ZERO GRAVITY,

00:04:28.133 --> 00:04:29.901
PLAYING IN THE NATIONAL
FOOTBALL LEAGUE,

00:04:29.901 --> 00:04:32.634
AUTHORING AN ARTICLE IN
THE "WORLD BOOK" ENCYCLOPEDIA--

00:04:32.634 --> 00:04:34.400
I GUESS YOU CAN TELL
THE NERDS EARLY--

00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:35.868
[laughter]

00:04:35.868 --> 00:04:37.634
BEING CAPTAIN KIRK.

00:04:37.634 --> 00:04:40.434
ANYBODY HERE
HAVE THAT CHILDHOOD DREAM?

00:04:40.434 --> 00:04:42.667
NOT AT CMU, NO.

00:04:42.667 --> 00:04:44.334
I WANTED TO BECOME
ONE OF THE GUYS

00:04:44.334 --> 00:04:46.501
WHO WON THE BIG STUFFED ANIMALS
IN THE AMUSEMENT PARK,

00:04:46.501 --> 00:04:48.801
AND I WANTED TO BE
AN IMAGINEER WITH DISNEY.

00:04:48.801 --> 00:04:50.634
THESE ARE NOT SORTED
IN ANY PARTICULAR ORDER,

00:04:50.634 --> 00:04:52.501
ALTHOUGH I THINK
THEY DO GET HARDER,

00:04:52.501 --> 00:04:54.801
EXCEPT FOR MAYBE THE FIRST ONE.

00:04:54.801 --> 00:04:56.734
OKAY SO BEING IN ZERO GRAVITY.

00:04:56.734 --> 00:04:58.534
NOW, IT'S IMPORTANT
TO HAVE SPECIFIC DREAMS.

00:04:58.534 --> 00:05:00.000
I DID NOT DREAM OF BEING
AN ASTRONAUT,

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:01.868
BECAUSE WHEN I WAS A LITTLE KID,
I WORE GLASSES,

00:05:01.868 --> 00:05:03.934
AND THEY TOLD ME "OH, ASTRONAUTS
CAN'T HAVE GLASSES."

00:05:03.934 --> 00:05:05.467
AND I WAS LIKE, "MM, I DIDN'T
REALLY WANT

00:05:05.467 --> 00:05:08.067
THE WHOLE ASTRONAUT GIG;
I JUST WANTED THE FLOATING."

00:05:08.067 --> 00:05:10.501
SO--AND AS A CHILD--

00:05:10.501 --> 00:05:14.167
[laughter]

00:05:14.167 --> 00:05:17.300
PROTOTYPE 0.0.

00:05:17.300 --> 00:05:21.567
BUT THAT DIDN'T WORK SO WELL,
AND IT TURNS OUT THAT NASA

00:05:21.567 --> 00:05:24.367
HAS SOMETHING CALLED
THE VOMIT COMET

00:05:24.367 --> 00:05:25.934
THAT THEY USE TO TRAIN
THE ASTRONAUTS,

00:05:25.934 --> 00:05:28.634
AND THIS THING DOES
PARABOLIC ARCS,

00:05:28.634 --> 00:05:29.968
AND AT THE TOP OF EACH ARC,

00:05:29.968 --> 00:05:31.868
YOU GET ABOUT 25 SECONDS
WHERE YOU'RE BALLISTIC

00:05:31.868 --> 00:05:35.000
AND YOU GET ABOUT A ROUGH
EQUIVALENT OF WEIGHTLESSNESS

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:36.200
FOR ABOUT 25 SECONDS.

00:05:36.200 --> 00:05:39.300
AND THERE IS A PROGRAM
WHERE COLLEGE STUDENTS

00:05:39.300 --> 00:05:41.534
CAN SUBMIT PROPOSALS,

00:05:41.534 --> 00:05:45.734
AND IF THEY WIN THE COMPETITION,
THEY GET TO FLY,

00:05:45.734 --> 00:05:47.234
AND I THOUGHT
THAT WAS REALLY COOL,

00:05:47.234 --> 00:05:48.934
AND WE HAD A TEAM,
AND WE PUT A TEAM TOGETHER,

00:05:48.934 --> 00:05:50.434
AND THEY WON,
AND THEY GOT TO FLY,

00:05:50.434 --> 00:05:53.667
AND I WAS ALL EXCITED BECAUSE
I WAS GOING TO GO WITH THEM...

00:05:53.667 --> 00:05:55.767
AND THEN I HIT
THE FIRST BRICK WALL,

00:05:55.767 --> 00:05:57.300
BECAUSE THEY MADE IT
VERY CLEAR

00:05:57.300 --> 00:06:00.934
THAT UNDER NO CIRCUMSTANCES
WERE FACULTY MEMBERS

00:06:00.934 --> 00:06:03.200
ALLOWED TO FLY
WITH THE TEAMS.

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:05.968
I KNOW.
I WAS HEARTBROKEN, RIGHT.

00:06:05.968 --> 00:06:10.634
I WAS LIKE, "BUT I WORKED
SO HARD."

00:06:10.634 --> 00:06:13.667
AND SO I READ THE LITERATURE
VERY CAREFULLY,

00:06:13.667 --> 00:06:15.467
AND IT TURNS OUT THAT NASA--

00:06:15.467 --> 00:06:18.167
IT'S PART OF THEIR OUTREACH
AND PUBLICITY PROGRAM,

00:06:18.167 --> 00:06:20.601
AND IT TURNS OUT
THAT THE STUDENTS WERE ALLOWED

00:06:20.601 --> 00:06:24.234
TO BRING A LOCAL MEDIA
JOURNALIST FROM THEIR HOMETOWN.

00:06:24.234 --> 00:06:27.133
[laughter]

00:06:32.434 --> 00:06:35.200
RANDY PAUSCH, WEB JOURNALIST.

00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:36.734
IT'S REALLY EASY
TO GET A PRESS PASS.

00:06:36.734 --> 00:06:40.100
SO I CALLED UP THE GUYS AT NASA,
AND I SAID,

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:41.934
"I NEED TO KNOW
WHERE TO FAX SOME DOCUMENTS."

00:06:41.934 --> 00:06:44.234
AND THEY SAID, "WHAT DOCUMENTS
ARE YOU GOING TO FAX US?"

00:06:44.234 --> 00:06:46.667
I SAID, "MY RESIGNATION
AS THE FACULTY ADVISOR

00:06:46.667 --> 00:06:50.734
AND MY APPLICATION
AS THE JOURNALIST."

00:06:50.734 --> 00:06:55.567
AND HE SAID, "THAT'S A LITTLE
TRANSPARENT, DON'T YOU THINK?"

00:06:55.567 --> 00:06:58.200
AND I SAID, "YEAH, BUT OUR
PROJECT IS VIRTUAL REALITY,

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:01.300
"AND WE'RE GOING TO BRING DOWN
A WHOLE BUNCH OF VR HEADSETS,

00:07:01.300 --> 00:07:03.300
"AND ALL THE STUDENTS
FROM ALL THE TEAMS

00:07:03.300 --> 00:07:04.467
"ARE GOING TO EXPERIENCE IT

00:07:04.467 --> 00:07:06.067
"AND ALL THOSE OTHER
REAL JOURNALISTS

00:07:06.067 --> 00:07:09.334
ARE GOING TO GET TO FILM IT."

00:07:09.334 --> 00:07:13.000
JIM FOLEY'S GOING,
"OH, YOU BASTARD, YES."

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.934
AND THE GUY SAID,
"HERE'S THE FAX NUMBER."

00:07:15.934 --> 00:07:18.434
SO--AND INDEED, WE KEPT
OUR END OF THE BARGAIN,

00:07:18.434 --> 00:07:20.133
AND THAT'S ONE OF THE THEMES
THAT YOU'LL HEAR

00:07:20.133 --> 00:07:21.400
LATER ON IN THE TALK

00:07:21.400 --> 00:07:23.334
IS HAVE SOMETHING TO BRING
TO THE TABLE, RIGHT,

00:07:23.334 --> 00:07:26.133
BECAUSE THAT WILL MAKE YOU
MORE WELCOMED.

00:07:26.133 --> 00:07:29.968
AND IF YOU'RE CURIOUS ABOUT
WHAT ZERO GRAVITY LOOKS LIKE,

00:07:29.968 --> 00:07:33.501
HOPEFULLY THE SOUND
WILL BE WORKING HERE.

00:07:36.367 --> 00:07:37.567
man: IT'S ON.

00:07:37.567 --> 00:07:40.834
woman: ALL RIGHT,
GO GET 'EM, MAZI.

00:07:40.834 --> 00:07:42.968
THIS IS FANTASTIC.

00:07:42.968 --> 00:07:44.200
IT'S JUST AMAZING.

00:07:44.200 --> 00:07:47.234
IT'S NOTHING LIKE I EXPECTED.

00:07:47.234 --> 00:07:48.601
Pausch: THERE I AM.

00:07:48.601 --> 00:07:51.868
[laughter]

00:07:51.868 --> 00:07:54.234
woman: THIS IS AWESOME.

00:07:54.234 --> 00:07:57.467
[laughs]

00:07:57.467 --> 00:07:58.701
YOU GOT ONE, MAZI.

00:07:58.701 --> 00:08:00.100
THAT'S GOOD.

00:08:00.100 --> 00:08:01.767
man: GOT A BALL FOR YOU, MAZ.

00:08:01.767 --> 00:08:04.234
[laughter]

00:08:04.234 --> 00:08:09.300
Pausch: YOU DO PAY THE PIPER
AT THE BOTTOM.

00:08:09.300 --> 00:08:13.400
SO CHILDHOOD DREAM NUMBER ONE,
CHECK.

00:08:13.400 --> 00:08:15.000
ALL RIGHT, LET'S TALK
ABOUT FOOTBALL.

00:08:15.000 --> 00:08:17.834
MY DREAM WAS TO PLAY
IN THE NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE,

00:08:17.834 --> 00:08:20.601
AND MOST OF YOU DON'T KNOW
THAT I ACTUALLY PLAYED--NO.

00:08:20.601 --> 00:08:22.901
[laughter]

00:08:22.901 --> 00:08:25.033
NO, I DID NOT MAKE IT
TO THE NATIONAL FOOTBALL LEAGUE,

00:08:25.033 --> 00:08:29.100
BUT I PROBABLY GOT MORE
FROM THAT DREAM

00:08:29.100 --> 00:08:30.801
AND NOT ACCOMPLISHING IT

00:08:30.801 --> 00:08:34.767
THAN I GOT FROM ANY OF THE ONES
THAT I DID ACCOMPLISH.

00:08:34.767 --> 00:08:36.067
I HAD A COACH.

00:08:36.067 --> 00:08:37.501
I SIGNED UP WHEN
I WAS NINE YEARS OLD.

00:08:37.501 --> 00:08:40.801
I WAS THE SMALLEST KID
IN THE LEAGUE BY FAR,

00:08:40.801 --> 00:08:43.367
AND I HAD A COACH, JIM GRAHAM,
WHO WAS 6'4".

00:08:43.367 --> 00:08:45.601
HE HAD PLAYED LINEBACKER
AT PENN STATE.

00:08:45.601 --> 00:08:49.000
HE WAS JUST THIS HULK OF A GUY,

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.033
AND HE WAS OLD SCHOOL,
I MEAN, REALLY OLD SCHOOL.

00:08:52.033 --> 00:08:54.267
LIKE, HE THOUGHT THE
FORWARD PASS WAS A TRICK PLAY.

00:08:54.267 --> 00:08:56.567
[laughter]

00:08:56.567 --> 00:08:58.601
AND HE SHOWED UP FOR PRACTICE
THE FIRST DAY,

00:08:58.601 --> 00:09:00.601
AND, YOU KNOW,
HE'S THIS BIG HULKING GUY.

00:09:00.601 --> 00:09:02.067
WE WERE ALL SCARED
TO DEATH OF HIM,

00:09:02.067 --> 00:09:05.067
AND HE HADN'T BROUGHT
ANY FOOTBALLS.

00:09:05.067 --> 00:09:08.534
HOW ARE WE GOING TO HAVE
PRACTICE WITHOUT ANY FOOTBALLS?

00:09:08.534 --> 00:09:10.534
AND ONE OF THE OTHER KIDS SAID,

00:09:10.534 --> 00:09:13.100
"EXCUSE ME, COACH,
BUT THERE'S NO FOOTBALL."

00:09:13.100 --> 00:09:15.000
AND COACH GRAHAM SAID,
"RIGHT, HOW MANY MEN

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:16.667
ARE ON A FOOTBALL FIELD
AT A TIME?"

00:09:16.667 --> 00:09:18.634
"11 ON A TEAM, 22."

00:09:18.634 --> 00:09:20.200
AND COACH GRAHAM SAID,

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:21.667
"ALL RIGHT, AND HOW MANY PEOPLE

00:09:21.667 --> 00:09:23.601
ARE TOUCHING THE FOOTBALL
AT ANY GIVEN TIME?"

00:09:23.601 --> 00:09:24.868
"ONE OF THEM."

00:09:24.868 --> 00:09:26.567
AND HE SAID, "RIGHT,
SO WE'RE GOING TO WORK

00:09:26.567 --> 00:09:29.334
ON WHAT THOSE OTHER 21 GUYS
ARE DOING."

00:09:29.334 --> 00:09:31.667
AND THAT'S A REALLY GOOD STORY,

00:09:31.667 --> 00:09:33.901
BECAUSE IT'S ALL ABOUT
FUNDAMENTALS, FUNDAMENTALS,

00:09:33.901 --> 00:09:35.300
FUNDAMENTALS, FUNDAMENTALS.

00:09:35.300 --> 00:09:36.901
YOU'VE GOT TO GET
THE FUNDAMENTALS DOWN,

00:09:36.901 --> 00:09:39.067
BECAUSE OTHERWISE THE FANCY
STUFF ISN'T GOING TO WORK.

00:09:39.067 --> 00:09:40.968
AND THE OTHER JIM GRAHAM STORY
I HAVE IS,

00:09:40.968 --> 00:09:42.067
THERE WAS ONE PRACTICE

00:09:42.067 --> 00:09:43.734
WHERE HE JUST RODE ME
ALL PRACTICE.

00:09:43.734 --> 00:09:45.934
JUST, "YOU'RE DOING THIS WRONG.
YOU'RE DOING THIS WRONG.

00:09:45.934 --> 00:09:47.334
"GO BACK AND DO IT AGAIN.
YOU OWE ME.

00:09:47.334 --> 00:09:48.934
YOU'RE DOING PUSH-UPS
AFTER PRACTICE."

00:09:48.934 --> 00:09:50.300
AND WHEN IT WAS ALL OVER,

00:09:50.300 --> 00:09:52.467
ONE OF THE OTHER ASSISTANT
COACHES CAME OVER AND SAID,

00:09:52.467 --> 00:09:54.634
"YEAH, COACH GRAHAM RODE YOU
PRETTY HARD, DIDN'T HE?"

00:09:54.634 --> 00:09:55.667
I SAID, "YEAH."

00:09:55.667 --> 00:09:56.868
HE SAID, "THAT'S A GOOD THING."

00:09:56.868 --> 00:09:58.834
HE SAID, "WHEN YOU'RE
SCREWING UP

00:09:58.834 --> 00:10:01.334
"AND NOBODY'S SAYING ANYTHING
TO YOU ANYMORE,

00:10:01.334 --> 00:10:05.000
THAT MEANS THEY GAVE UP."

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:07.100
AND THAT'S A LESSON THAT STUCK
WITH ME MY WHOLE LIFE

00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:09.968
IS THAT WHEN YOU SEE YOURSELF
DOING SOMETHING BADLY

00:10:09.968 --> 00:10:12.033
AND NOBODY'S BOTHERING
TO TELL YOU ANYMORE,

00:10:12.033 --> 00:10:13.868
THAT'S A VERY BAD PLACE TO BE.

00:10:13.868 --> 00:10:15.534
YOUR CRITICS ARE YOUR ONES
TELLING YOU

00:10:15.534 --> 00:10:17.300
THEY STILL LOVE YOU AND CARE.

00:10:17.300 --> 00:10:18.968
AFTER COACH GRAHAM,
I HAD ANOTHER COACH,

00:10:18.968 --> 00:10:20.267
COACH SETLIFF,

00:10:20.267 --> 00:10:22.367
AND HE TAUGHT ME A LOT ABOUT
THE POWER OF ENTHUSIASM.

00:10:22.367 --> 00:10:25.000
HE DID THIS ONE THING WHERE
ONLY FOR ONE PLAY AT A TIME,

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:26.434
HE WOULD PUT PEOPLE IN
AT, LIKE,

00:10:26.434 --> 00:10:29.801
THE MOST HORRIFICALLY WRONG
POSITION FOR THEM.

00:10:29.801 --> 00:10:33.300
LIKE, ALL THE SHORT GUYS
WOULD BECOME RECEIVERS, RIGHT?

00:10:33.300 --> 00:10:34.601
IT WAS JUST LAUGHABLE.

00:10:34.601 --> 00:10:37.667
BUT WE ONLY WENT IN
FOR ONE PLAY, RIGHT?

00:10:37.667 --> 00:10:40.601
AND, BOY, THE OTHER TEAM
JUST NEVER KNEW WHAT HIT 'EM,

00:10:40.601 --> 00:10:42.534
BECAUSE WHEN YOU'RE
ONLY DOING IT FOR ONE PLAY

00:10:42.534 --> 00:10:44.367
AND YOU'RE JUST NOT WHERE
YOU'RE SUPPOSED TO BE

00:10:44.367 --> 00:10:46.567
AND FREEDOM'S JUST ANOTHER WORD
FOR NOTHING LEFT TO LOSE,

00:10:46.567 --> 00:10:48.334
BOY, ARE YOU GOING
TO CLEAN SOMEBODY'S CLOCK

00:10:48.334 --> 00:10:49.901
FOR THAT ONE PLAY.

00:10:49.901 --> 00:10:51.667
AND THAT KIND OF ENTHUSIASM
WAS GREAT,

00:10:51.667 --> 00:10:54.601
AND TO THIS DAY, I AM MOST
COMFORTABLE ON A FOOTBALL FIELD.

00:10:54.601 --> 00:10:56.634
I MEAN, IT'S JUST ONE
OF THOSE THINGS WHERE,

00:10:56.634 --> 00:10:58.467
YOU KNOW, IF I'M WORKING
A HARD PROBLEM,

00:10:58.467 --> 00:11:00.167
PEOPLE WILL SEE ME WANDERING
THE HALLS

00:11:00.167 --> 00:11:02.567
WITH ONE OF THESE THINGS,
AND THAT'S JUST BECAUSE,

00:11:02.567 --> 00:11:04.434
YOU KNOW, WHEN YOU DO SOMETHING
YOUNG ENOUGH

00:11:04.434 --> 00:11:05.667
AND YOU TRAIN FOR IT,

00:11:05.667 --> 00:11:07.067
IT JUST BECOMES
A PART OF YOU,

00:11:07.067 --> 00:11:09.801
AND I'M VERY GLAD THAT FOOTBALL
WAS A PART OF MY LIFE,

00:11:09.801 --> 00:11:11.901
AND IF I DIDN'T GET THE DREAM
OF PLAYING IN THE NFL,

00:11:11.901 --> 00:11:13.067
THAT'S OKAY.

00:11:13.067 --> 00:11:15.033
I PROBABLY GOT STUFF
MORE VALUABLE,

00:11:15.033 --> 00:11:17.100
BECAUSE LOOKING AT WHAT'S
GOING ON IN THE NFL,

00:11:17.100 --> 00:11:20.100
I'M NOT SURE THOSE GUYS
ARE DOING SO GREAT RIGHT NOW.

00:11:20.100 --> 00:11:21.501
OKAY.

00:11:21.501 --> 00:11:23.000
AND SO ONE OF THE EXPRESSIONS

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.667
I LEARNED AT ELECTRONIC ARTS,
WHICH I LOVE,

00:11:24.667 --> 00:11:26.834
WHICH PERTAINS TO THIS IS,
"EXPERIENCE IS WHAT YOU GET

00:11:26.834 --> 00:11:29.167
WHEN YOU DIDN'T GET
WHAT YOU WANTED."

00:11:29.167 --> 00:11:32.033
AND I THINK THAT'S
ABSOLUTELY LOVELY.

00:11:32.033 --> 00:11:33.901
AND THE OTHER THING
ABOUT FOOTBALL IS,

00:11:33.901 --> 00:11:36.434
WE SEND OUR KIDS OUT
TO PLAY FOOTBALL OR SOCCER

00:11:36.434 --> 00:11:37.968
OR SWIMMING OR WHATEVER IT IS,

00:11:37.968 --> 00:11:40.000
AND IT'S THE FIRST EXAMPLE
OF WHAT I'M GOING TO CALL

00:11:40.000 --> 00:11:41.501
A HEAD FAKE
OR INDIRECT LEARNING.

00:11:41.501 --> 00:11:43.434
WE ACTUALLY DON'T WANT OUR KIDS
TO LEARN FOOTBALL.

00:11:43.434 --> 00:11:44.601
I MEAN, YEAH, IT'S REALLY NICE

00:11:44.601 --> 00:11:46.267
THAT I HAVE A WONDERFUL
THREE-POINT STANCE

00:11:46.267 --> 00:11:47.667
AND THAT I KNOW HOW TO DO
A CHOP BLOCK

00:11:47.667 --> 00:11:48.667
AND ALL THIS KIND OF STUFF.

00:11:48.667 --> 00:11:50.100
BUT WE SEND OUR KIDS
OUT TO LEARN

00:11:50.100 --> 00:11:51.901
MUCH MORE IMPORTANT THINGS:

00:11:51.901 --> 00:11:54.601
TEAMWORK, SPORTSMANSHIP,
PERSEVERANCE, ET CETERA,

00:11:54.601 --> 00:11:55.801
ET CETERA.

00:11:55.801 --> 00:11:58.100
AND THESE KINDS
OF HEAD FAKE LEARNINGS

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:00.801
ARE ABSOLUTELY IMPORTANT,

00:12:00.801 --> 00:12:02.467
AND YOU SHOULD KEEP
YOUR EYE OUT FOR THEM,

00:12:02.467 --> 00:12:04.000
BECAUSE THEY'RE EVERYWHERE.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:05.400
ALL RIGHT, A SIMPLE ONE,

00:12:05.400 --> 00:12:07.634
BEING AN AUTHOR IN
THE "WORLD BOOK" ENCYCLOPEDIA.

00:12:07.634 --> 00:12:08.968
WHEN I WAS A KID,

00:12:08.968 --> 00:12:11.033
WE HAD THE "WORLD BOOK"
ENCYCLOPEDIA ON THE SHELF.

00:12:11.033 --> 00:12:12.968
FOR THE FRESHMEN,
THIS IS PAPER.

00:12:12.968 --> 00:12:15.934
[laughter]

00:12:15.934 --> 00:12:20.868
WE USED TO HAVE THESE THINGS
CALLED BOOKS.

00:12:20.868 --> 00:12:23.467
AND AFTER I HAD BECOME SOMEWHAT
OF AN AUTHORITY

00:12:23.467 --> 00:12:24.868
ON VIRTUAL REALITY,
BUT NOT, LIKE,

00:12:24.868 --> 00:12:26.300
A REALLY IMPORTANT ONE--

00:12:26.300 --> 00:12:29.767
SO I WAS AT THE LEVEL OF PEOPLE
THE "WORLD BOOK" WOULD BADGER--

00:12:29.767 --> 00:12:31.400
THEY CALLED ME UP,
AND I WROTE AN ARTICLE,

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:33.000
AND THIS IS CAITLIN KELLEHER.

00:12:33.000 --> 00:12:35.868
AND THERE'S AN ARTICLE IF YOU GO
TO YOUR LOCAL LIBRARY

00:12:35.868 --> 00:12:37.968
WHERE THEY STILL HAVE COPIES
OF THE "WORLD BOOK."

00:12:37.968 --> 00:12:39.534
LOOK UNDER "V"
FOR VIRTUAL REALITY,

00:12:39.534 --> 00:12:40.534
AND THERE IT IS.

00:12:40.534 --> 00:12:43.000
AND ALL I HAVE TO SAY
IS THAT,

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:44.767
HAVING BEEN SELECTED
TO BE AN AUTHOR

00:12:44.767 --> 00:12:46.601
IN THE "WORLD BOOK"
ENCYCLOPEDIA,

00:12:46.601 --> 00:12:49.767
I NOW BELIEVE THAT WIKIPEDIA
IS A PERFECTLY FINE SOURCE

00:12:49.767 --> 00:12:50.968
FOR YOUR INFORMATION

00:12:50.968 --> 00:12:52.901
BECAUSE I KNOW WHAT
THE QUALITY CONTROL IS

00:12:52.901 --> 00:12:54.267
FOR REAL ENCYCLOPEDIAS.

00:12:54.267 --> 00:12:56.834
THEY LET ME IN.

00:12:56.834 --> 00:12:58.868
ALL RIGHT, NEXT ONE.

00:12:58.868 --> 00:13:01.868
[laughter]

00:13:04.167 --> 00:13:05.634
AT A CERTAIN POINT,
YOU JUST REALIZE

00:13:05.634 --> 00:13:07.367
THERE ARE SOME THINGS
YOU ARE NOT GOING TO DO,

00:13:07.367 --> 00:13:10.400
SO MAYBE YOU JUST WANT TO STAND
CLOSE TO THE PEOPLE.

00:13:14.801 --> 00:13:20.267
I MEAN, MY GOD, WHAT
A ROLE MODEL FOR YOUNG PEOPLE.

00:13:20.267 --> 00:13:22.801
I MEAN, THIS IS EVERYTHING
YOU WANT TO BE,

00:13:22.801 --> 00:13:24.801
AND WHAT I LEARNED
THAT CARRIED ME FORWARD

00:13:24.801 --> 00:13:26.200
IN LEADERSHIP LATER IS THAT,

00:13:26.200 --> 00:13:28.033
YOU KNOW, HE WASN'T THE SMARTEST
GUY ON THE SHIP.

00:13:28.033 --> 00:13:29.501
I MEAN, SPOCK WAS PRETTY SMART,

00:13:29.501 --> 00:13:32.067
AND MCCOY WAS THE DOCTOR,
AND SCOTTY WAS THE ENGINEER,

00:13:32.067 --> 00:13:34.601
AND YOU SORT OF GO,
"AND WHAT SKILL SET DID HE HAVE

00:13:34.601 --> 00:13:36.934
TO GET ON THIS DAMN THING
AND RUN IT?"

00:13:36.934 --> 00:13:38.367
AND, YOU KNOW,
CLEARLY THERE IS

00:13:38.367 --> 00:13:40.033
THIS SKILL SET CALLED
LEADERSHIP,

00:13:40.033 --> 00:13:42.334
AND, YOU KNOW, WHETHER OR NOT
YOU LIKE THE SERIES,

00:13:42.334 --> 00:13:44.467
THERE'S NO DOUBT THAT THERE WAS
A LOT TO BE LEARNED

00:13:44.467 --> 00:13:48.467
ABOUT HOW TO LEAD PEOPLE
BY WATCHING THIS GUY IN ACTION,

00:13:48.467 --> 00:13:52.901
AND HE JUST HAD THE COOLEST
DAMN TOYS.

00:13:52.901 --> 00:13:56.968
I MEAN, MY GOD, HE, YOU KNOW--

00:13:56.968 --> 00:13:58.601
I JUST THOUGHT IT WAS
FASCINATING AS A KID

00:13:58.601 --> 00:14:00.767
THAT HE HAD THIS THING
AND HE COULD,

00:14:00.767 --> 00:14:02.567
YOU KNOW, TALK TO THE SHIP
WITH IT.

00:14:02.567 --> 00:14:04.934
[electronic beeping]

00:14:04.934 --> 00:14:06.801
I JUST THOUGHT
THAT WAS JUST SPECTACULAR,

00:14:06.801 --> 00:14:12.234
AND OF COURSE NOW I OWN ONE,
AND IT'S SMALLER.

00:14:12.234 --> 00:14:15.834
SO THAT'S KIND OF COOL.

00:14:15.834 --> 00:14:21.067
SO I GOT TO ACHIEVE THIS DREAM.

00:14:21.067 --> 00:14:26.133
JAMES T. KIRK--HIS ALTER EGO
WILLIAM SHATNER WROTE A BOOK,

00:14:26.133 --> 00:14:28.167
WHICH I THINK WAS ACTUALLY
A PRETTY COOL BOOK.

00:14:28.167 --> 00:14:29.534
IT WAS WITH CHIP WALTER,

00:14:29.534 --> 00:14:32.367
WHO IS A PITTSBURGH-BASED
AUTHOR WHO IS QUITE GOOD,

00:14:32.367 --> 00:14:34.067
AND THEY WROTE A BOOK
ON BASICALLY

00:14:34.067 --> 00:14:35.501
THE SCIENCE OF STAR TREK,
YOU KNOW,

00:14:35.501 --> 00:14:37.067
WHAT HAS COME TRUE,

00:14:37.067 --> 00:14:39.434
AND THEY WENT AROUND TO THE
TOP PLACES AROUND THE COUNTRY

00:14:39.434 --> 00:14:40.801
AND LOOKED AT VARIOUS THINGS,

00:14:40.801 --> 00:14:42.934
AND THEY CAME HERE TO STUDY
OUR VIRTUAL REALITY SETUP,

00:14:42.934 --> 00:14:45.567
AND SO WE BUILT
A VIRTUAL REALITY FOR HIM.

00:14:45.567 --> 00:14:47.400
IT LOOKS SOMETHING LIKE THAT.

00:14:47.400 --> 00:14:49.033
WE PUT IT IN,
PUT IT TO RED ALERT.

00:14:49.033 --> 00:14:50.367
HE WAS A VERY GOOD SPORT.

00:14:50.367 --> 00:14:55.334
IT'S NOT LIKE HE SAW
THAT ONE COMING.

00:14:55.334 --> 00:15:01.000
AND IT'S REALLY COOL
TO MEET YOUR BOYHOOD IDOL,

00:15:01.000 --> 00:15:03.834
BUT IT'S EVEN COOLER
WHEN HE COMES TO YOU

00:15:03.834 --> 00:15:08.234
TO SEE WHAT COOL STUFF
YOU'RE DOING IN YOUR LAB,

00:15:08.234 --> 00:15:11.133
AND THAT WAS JUST
A GREAT MOMENT.

00:15:11.133 --> 00:15:16.300
ALL RIGHT,
WINNING STUFFED ANIMALS.

00:15:16.300 --> 00:15:17.901
THIS MAY SEEM MUNDANE TO YOU,

00:15:17.901 --> 00:15:20.067
BUT WHEN YOU'RE A LITTLE KID
AND YOU SEE THE BIG BUFF GUYS

00:15:20.067 --> 00:15:21.501
WALKING AROUND
AN AMUSEMENT PARK

00:15:21.501 --> 00:15:23.634
AND THEY'VE GOT ALL THESE
BIG STUFFED ANIMALS, RIGHT?

00:15:23.634 --> 00:15:25.200
AND THIS IS MY LOVELY WIFE,

00:15:25.200 --> 00:15:29.634
AND I HAVE A LOT OF PICTURES
OF STUFFED ANIMALS I'VE WON.

00:15:29.634 --> 00:15:33.767
THAT'S MY DAD POSING WITH ONE
THAT I WON.

00:15:33.767 --> 00:15:36.267
I'VE WON A LOT OF THESE ANIMALS.

00:15:36.267 --> 00:15:37.601
THERE'S MY DAD.

00:15:37.601 --> 00:15:39.801
HE DID WIN THAT ONE
TO HIS CREDIT.

00:15:39.801 --> 00:15:42.734
[laughter]

00:15:47.200 --> 00:15:48.467
RIGHT, AND THIS WAS JUST

00:15:48.467 --> 00:15:50.067
A BIG PART OF MY LIFE
AND MY FAMILY'S LIFE,

00:15:50.067 --> 00:15:52.234
BUT, YOU KNOW,
I CAN HEAR THE CYNICS.

00:15:52.234 --> 00:15:55.901
YOU KNOW, IN THIS AGE
OF DIGITALLY MANIPULATED THINGS,

00:15:55.901 --> 00:15:58.834
MAYBE THOSE BEARS REALLY AREN'T
IN THE PICTURES WITH ME,

00:15:58.834 --> 00:16:01.634
OR MAYBE I PAID SOMEBODY
FIVE BUCKS

00:16:01.634 --> 00:16:03.901
TO TAKE A PICTURE IN
THE THEME PARK NEXT TO THE BEAR.

00:16:03.901 --> 00:16:05.834
AND I SAID, "HOW, IN THIS AGE
OF CYNICISM,

00:16:05.834 --> 00:16:07.667
CAN I CONVINCE PEOPLE?"

00:16:07.667 --> 00:16:11.234
AND I SAID, "I KNOW.
I CAN SHOW THEM THE BEARS."

00:16:11.234 --> 00:16:16.067
BRING THEM OUT.

00:16:16.067 --> 00:16:19.968
[applause]

00:16:19.968 --> 00:16:22.200
IF YOU CAN JUST PUT 'EM
RIGHT THERE.

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:26.701
JUST PUT THEM BACK
AGAINST THE WALL.

00:16:26.701 --> 00:16:30.968
woman: IT'S HARD TO HEAR YOU.

00:16:30.968 --> 00:16:35.501
Pausch: THANKS, HONEY.

00:16:35.501 --> 00:16:38.300
SO HERE ARE SOME BEARS.

00:16:38.300 --> 00:16:40.467
WE DIDN'T HAVE QUITE ENOUGH ROOM
IN THE MOVING TRUCK

00:16:40.467 --> 00:16:42.167
DOWN TO CHESAPEAKE,

00:16:42.167 --> 00:16:44.701
AND ANYBODY WHO WOULD LIKE
A LITTLE PIECE OF ME

00:16:44.701 --> 00:16:47.234
AT THE END OF THIS,
FEEL FREE TO COME UP.

00:16:47.234 --> 00:16:50.067
FIRST COME, FIRST SERVE.

00:16:50.067 --> 00:16:53.734
ALL RIGHT, MY NEXT ONE,
BEING AN IMAGINEER.

00:16:53.734 --> 00:16:55.200
THIS WAS THE HARD ONE.

00:16:55.200 --> 00:16:57.100
BELIEVE ME,
GETTING TO ZERO GRAVITY

00:16:57.100 --> 00:16:59.934
IS EASIER THAN BECOMING
AN IMAGINEER.

00:16:59.934 --> 00:17:02.934
WHEN I WAS A KID,
I WAS EIGHT YEARS OLD

00:17:02.934 --> 00:17:04.734
AND OUR FAMILY TOOK
A TRIP CROSS-COUNTRY

00:17:04.734 --> 00:17:07.300
TO SEE DISNEYLAND, AND IF YOU'VE
EVER SEEN THE MOVIE

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:11.767
"NATIONAL LAMPOON'S VACATION,"
IT WAS A LOT LIKE THAT.

00:17:11.767 --> 00:17:13.834
IT WAS A QUEST.

00:17:13.834 --> 00:17:17.801
AND THESE ARE REAL
VINTAGE PHOTOGRAPHS,

00:17:17.801 --> 00:17:20.868
AND THERE I AM

00:17:20.868 --> 00:17:23.133
IN FRONT OF THE CASTLE,
AND THERE I AM--

00:17:23.133 --> 00:17:25.133
AND FOR THOSE OF YOU
WHO ARE INTO FORESHADOWING,

00:17:25.133 --> 00:17:28.567
THIS IS THE ALICE RIDE.

00:17:28.567 --> 00:17:33.033
AND I JUST THOUGHT THIS WAS JUST
THE COOLEST ENVIRONMENT

00:17:33.033 --> 00:17:34.601
I HAD EVER BEEN IN,
AND INSTEAD OF SAYING,

00:17:34.601 --> 00:17:36.200
"GEE, I WANT
TO EXPERIENCE THIS," I SAID,

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:38.133
"I WANT TO MAKE STUFF
LIKE THIS."

00:17:38.133 --> 00:17:40.267
AND SO I BIDED MY TIME,

00:17:40.267 --> 00:17:41.667
AND THEN I GRADUATED
WITH MY PhD

00:17:41.667 --> 00:17:43.567
FROM CARNEGIE MELLON,
THINKING THAT MEANT ME

00:17:43.567 --> 00:17:45.167
INFINITELY QUALIFIED
TO DO ANYTHING,

00:17:45.167 --> 00:17:46.934
AND I DASHED OFF MY LETTERS
OF APPLICATION

00:17:46.934 --> 00:17:48.400
TO WALT DISNEY IMAGINEERING,

00:17:48.400 --> 00:17:51.100
AND THEY SENT ME SOME OF THE
DAMNED NICEST GO-TO-HELL LETTERS

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:53.400
I HAVE EVER GOTTEN.

00:17:53.400 --> 00:17:55.734
I MEAN IT WAS JUST--

00:17:55.734 --> 00:17:58.434
"WE HAVE CAREFULLY REVIEWED
YOUR APPLICATION,

00:17:58.434 --> 00:18:01.801
"AND PRESENTLY WE DO NOT HAVE
ANY POSITIONS AVAILABLE

00:18:01.801 --> 00:18:05.200
WHICH REQUIRE
YOUR PARTICULAR QUALIFICATIONS."

00:18:05.200 --> 00:18:07.701
NOW, THINK ABOUT THE FACT THAT
YOU'RE GETTING THIS FROM A PLACE

00:18:07.701 --> 00:18:11.901
THAT'S FAMOUS FOR GUYS
WHO SWEEP THE STREET.

00:18:11.901 --> 00:18:14.367
SO THAT WAS A BIT OF A SETBACK.

00:18:14.367 --> 00:18:18.634
BUT REMEMBER, THE BRICK WALLS
ARE THERE FOR A REASON.

00:18:18.634 --> 00:18:20.834
ALL RIGHT, THE BRICK WALLS
ARE NOT THERE TO KEEP US OUT.

00:18:20.834 --> 00:18:23.167
THE BRICK WALLS ARE THERE
TO GIVE US A CHANCE

00:18:23.167 --> 00:18:26.167
TO SHOW HOW BADLY
WE WANT SOMETHING,

00:18:26.167 --> 00:18:28.234
BECAUSE THE BRICK WALLS
ARE THERE TO STOP THE PEOPLE

00:18:28.234 --> 00:18:30.767
WHO DON'T WANT IT
BADLY ENOUGH.

00:18:30.767 --> 00:18:35.434
THEY'RE THERE TO STOP
THE OTHER PEOPLE.

00:18:35.434 --> 00:18:37.734
ALL RIGHT,
FAST FORWARD TO 1991.

00:18:37.734 --> 00:18:39.734
WE DID A SYSTEM BACK
AT THE UNIVERSITY OF VIRGINIA

00:18:39.734 --> 00:18:42.234
CALLED VIRTUAL REALITY
ON $5 A DAY,

00:18:42.234 --> 00:18:45.400
JUST ONE OF THOSE UNBELIEVABLE
SPECTACULAR THINGS.

00:18:45.400 --> 00:18:48.801
I WAS SO SCARED BACK IN
THOSE DAYS AS A JUNIOR ACADEMIC.

00:18:48.801 --> 00:18:51.534
JIM FOLEY'S HERE, AND I JUST
LOVE TO TELL THIS STORY.

00:18:51.534 --> 00:18:53.834
HE KNEW MY UNDERGRADUATE
ADVISOR, ANDY VAN DAM,

00:18:53.834 --> 00:18:56.267
AND I'M AT MY FIRST CONFERENCE,
AND I'M JUST SCARED TO DEATH,

00:18:56.267 --> 00:18:59.601
AND THIS ICON
IN THE USER INTERFACE COMMUNITY

00:18:59.601 --> 00:19:01.100
WALKS UP TO ME
AND JUST OUT OF NOWHERE

00:19:01.100 --> 00:19:02.534
JUST GIVES ME
THIS HUGE BEAR HUG,

00:19:02.534 --> 00:19:05.234
AND HE SAYS,
"THAT WAS FROM ANDY."

00:19:05.234 --> 00:19:08.300
AND THAT WAS WHEN I THOUGHT,
"OKAY, MAYBE I CAN MAKE IT.

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:10.767
ALL RIGHT, YOU KNOW,
MAYBE I DO BELONG."

00:19:10.767 --> 00:19:12.133
AND A SIMILAR STORY

00:19:12.133 --> 00:19:13.801
IS THAT THIS WAS JUST
THIS UNBELIEVABLE HIT

00:19:13.801 --> 00:19:15.167
BECAUSE AT THE TIME,

00:19:15.167 --> 00:19:17.501
EVERYBODY NEEDED $1/2 MILLION
TO DO VIRTUAL REALITY,

00:19:17.501 --> 00:19:18.834
AND EVERYBODY FELT FRUSTRATED,

00:19:18.834 --> 00:19:20.534
AND WE LITERALLY
HACKED TOGETHER A SYSTEM

00:19:20.534 --> 00:19:23.767
FOR ABOUT $5,000 IN PARTS
AND MADE A WORKING VR SYSTEM,

00:19:23.767 --> 00:19:25.234
AND PEOPLE WERE JUST LIKE,
"OH MY GOD,

00:19:25.234 --> 00:19:27.534
THIS IS LIKE , YOU KNOW, THE
HEWLETT-PACKARD GARAGE THING.

00:19:27.534 --> 00:19:29.033
THIS IS SO AWESOME."

00:19:29.033 --> 00:19:31.367
AND SO I'M GIVING THIS TALK,
AND THE ROOM HAS JUST GONE WILD,

00:19:31.367 --> 00:19:33.067
AND DURING THE Q&amp;A,
A GUY NAMED TOM FURNESS,

00:19:33.067 --> 00:19:35.968
WHO WAS ONE OF THE BIG NAMES
IN VIRTUAL REALITY AT THE TIME,

00:19:35.968 --> 00:19:38.133
HE GOES UP TO THE MICROPHONE,
AND HE INTRODUCES HIMSELF.

00:19:38.133 --> 00:19:39.534
I DIDN'T KNOW
WHAT HE LOOKED LIKE,

00:19:39.534 --> 00:19:40.801
BUT I SURE AS HELL
KNEW THE NAME.

00:19:40.801 --> 00:19:42.367
AND HE ASKED A QUESTION,
AND I WAS LIKE,

00:19:42.367 --> 00:19:44.767
"I'M SORRY, DID YOU SAY
YOU'RE TOM FURNESS?"

00:19:44.767 --> 00:19:46.067
AND HE SAID, "YES."

00:19:46.067 --> 00:19:48.033
I SAID, "THEN I WOULD LOVE
TO ANSWER YOUR QUESTION,

00:19:48.033 --> 00:19:50.033
BUT FIRST, WILL YOU
HAVE LUNCH WITH ME TOMORROW?"

00:19:50.033 --> 00:19:52.200
[laughter]

00:19:52.200 --> 00:19:55.767
AND THERE'S A LOT
IN THAT LITTLE MOMENT.

00:19:55.767 --> 00:19:57.234
RIGHT, THERE'S A LOT
OF HUMILITY

00:19:57.234 --> 00:20:00.234
BUT ALSO ASKING A PERSON
WHERE HE CAN'T POSSIBLY SAY NO.

00:20:00.234 --> 00:20:03.167
[laughter]

00:20:06.734 --> 00:20:09.200
AND SO IMAGINEERING
A COUPLE OF YEARS LATER

00:20:09.200 --> 00:20:10.868
WAS WORKING ON
A VIRTUAL REALITY PROJECT.

00:20:10.868 --> 00:20:12.300
THIS WAS TOP SECRET.

00:20:12.300 --> 00:20:15.701
THEY WERE DENYING THE EXISTENCE
OF A VIRTUAL REALITY ATTRACTION

00:20:15.701 --> 00:20:18.067
AFTER THE TIME
THAT THE PUBLICITY DEPARTMENT

00:20:18.067 --> 00:20:20.067
WAS RUNNING THE TV COMMERCIALS.

00:20:20.067 --> 00:20:23.300
SO IMAGINEERING REALLY
HAD NAILED THIS ONE TIGHT.

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:25.033
AND IT WAS
THE ALADDIN ATTRACTION

00:20:25.033 --> 00:20:26.701
WHERE YOU WOULD FLY
A MAGIC CARPET,

00:20:26.701 --> 00:20:31.133
AND THE HEAD-MOUNTED DISPLAY,
SOMETIMES KNOWN AS GATOR VISION.

00:20:31.133 --> 00:20:33.834
AND SO I HAD AN IN.

00:20:33.834 --> 00:20:36.133
AS SOON AS THE PROJECT
HAD JUST--

00:20:36.133 --> 00:20:38.133
YOU KNOW, THEY STARTED RUNNING
THE TV COMMERCIALS,

00:20:38.133 --> 00:20:41.100
AND I HAD BEEN ASKED TO BRIEF
THE SECRETARY OF DEFENSE

00:20:41.100 --> 00:20:42.367
ON THE STATE OF VIRTUAL REALITY.

00:20:42.367 --> 00:20:45.734
OKAY, FRED BROOKS
AND I HAD BEEN ASKED

00:20:45.734 --> 00:20:47.834
TO BRIEF THE SECRETARY
OF DEFENSE,

00:20:47.834 --> 00:20:51.400
AND THAT GAVE ME AN EXCUSE.

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:52.534
SO I CALLED THEM UP.

00:20:52.534 --> 00:20:54.133
I CALLED IMAGINEERING,
AND I SAID,

00:20:54.133 --> 00:20:56.000
"LOOK, I'M BRIEFING
THE SECRETARY OF DEFENSE.

00:20:56.000 --> 00:20:57.667
I'D LIKE SOME MATERIALS
ON WHAT YOU HAVE,

00:20:57.667 --> 00:20:59.734
BECAUSE IT'S ONE OF THE BEST
VR SYSTEMS IN THE WORLD."

00:20:59.734 --> 00:21:01.000
AND THEY KIND OF PUSHED BACK.

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:02.901
AND I SAID, "LOOK, IS ALL
THIS PATRIOTISM STUFF

00:21:02.901 --> 00:21:04.234
IN THE PARKS A FARCE?"

00:21:04.234 --> 00:21:07.467
AND THEY'RE LIKE, "HMM, OKAY,"
BUT THEY SAID,

00:21:07.467 --> 00:21:09.300
"BUT THE PR DEPARTMENT DOESN'T--
THIS IS SO NEW,

00:21:09.300 --> 00:21:11.367
"THE PR DEPARTMENT DOESN'T HAVE
ANY FOOTAGE FOR YOU,

00:21:11.367 --> 00:21:12.868
"SO I'M GOING
TO HAVE TO CONNECT YOU

00:21:12.868 --> 00:21:14.901
STRAIGHT THROUGH TO THE TEAM
WHO DID THE WORK."

00:21:14.901 --> 00:21:16.934
JACKPOT.

00:21:16.934 --> 00:21:19.300
SO I FIND MYSELF ON THE PHONE
WITH A GUY NAMED JON SNODDY

00:21:19.300 --> 00:21:21.634
WHO IS ONE OF THE MOST
IMPRESSIVE GUYS

00:21:21.634 --> 00:21:22.968
I HAVE EVER MET,

00:21:22.968 --> 00:21:24.634
AND HE WAS THE GUY
RUNNING THIS TEAM,

00:21:24.634 --> 00:21:27.167
AND IT'S NOT SURPRISING
THEY HAD DONE IMPRESSIVE THINGS.

00:21:27.167 --> 00:21:28.901
AND SO HE SENT ME SOME STUFF.

00:21:28.901 --> 00:21:30.000
WE TALKED BRIEFLY.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:31.300
HE SENT ME SOME STUFF,
AND I SAID,

00:21:31.300 --> 00:21:32.701
"HEY, I'M GOING TO BE OUT
IN THE AREA

00:21:32.701 --> 00:21:33.901
"FOR A CONFERENCE SHORTLY.

00:21:33.901 --> 00:21:35.701
WOULD YOU LIKE TO GET TOGETHER
AND HAVE LUNCH?"

00:21:35.701 --> 00:21:37.767
TRANSLATION: "I'M GOING
TO LIE TO YOU

00:21:37.767 --> 00:21:39.534
"AND SAY THAT I HAVE AN EXCUSE
TO BE IN THE AREA

00:21:39.534 --> 00:21:41.501
"SO I DON'T LOOK TOO ANXIOUS,

00:21:41.501 --> 00:21:45.300
BUT I WOULD GO TO NEPTUNE
TO HAVE LUNCH WITH YOU."

00:21:45.300 --> 00:21:49.434
AND SO JON SAID, "SURE,"

00:21:49.434 --> 00:21:53.367
AND I SPENT SOMETHING LIKE
80 HOURS

00:21:53.367 --> 00:21:56.367
TALKING WITH ALL THE VR EXPERTS
IN THE WORLD, SAYING,

00:21:56.367 --> 00:21:59.367
"IF YOU HAD ACCESS TO THIS ONE
UNBELIEVABLE PROJECT,

00:21:59.367 --> 00:22:01.033
WHAT WOULD YOU ASK?"

00:22:01.033 --> 00:22:03.267
AND THEN I COMPILED ALL OF THAT,
AND I HAD TO MEMORIZE IT,

00:22:03.267 --> 00:22:05.567
WHICH ANYBODY WHO KNOWS ME KNOWS
THAT I HAVE NO MEMORY AT ALL,

00:22:05.567 --> 00:22:07.567
BECAUSE I COULDN'T GO IN LOOKING
LIKE A DWEEB WITH,

00:22:07.567 --> 00:22:09.467
YOU KNOW, "HI, QUESTION 72."

00:22:09.467 --> 00:22:12.934
SO I WENT IN, AND THIS WAS,
LIKE, A TWO-HOUR LUNCH,

00:22:12.934 --> 00:22:14.267
AND JON MUST HAVE THOUGHT

00:22:14.267 --> 00:22:17.400
HE WAS TALKING
TO SOME PHENOMENAL PERSON,

00:22:17.400 --> 00:22:20.033
BECAUSE ALL I WAS DOING
WAS CHANNELING FRED BROOKS

00:22:20.033 --> 00:22:21.667
AND IVAN SUTHERLAND
AND ANDY VAN DAM

00:22:21.667 --> 00:22:23.300
AND PEOPLE LIKE THAT,
AND HENRY FUCHS.

00:22:23.300 --> 00:22:24.968
SO IT'S PRETTY EASY TO BE SMART

00:22:24.968 --> 00:22:28.234
WHEN YOU'RE PARROTING
SMART PEOPLE.

00:22:28.234 --> 00:22:31.467
AND AT THE END OF THE LUNCH
WITH JON, I SORT OF,

00:22:31.467 --> 00:22:33.801
AS WE SAY IN THE BUSINESS,
MADE "THE ASK."

00:22:33.801 --> 00:22:37.801
AND I SAID, "YOU KNOW,
I HAVE A SABBATICAL COMING UP."

00:22:37.801 --> 00:22:38.968
AND HE SAID, "WHAT'S THAT?"

00:22:38.968 --> 00:22:41.901
[laughter]

00:22:43.868 --> 00:22:47.334
THE BEGINNINGS
OF THE CULTURE CLASH.

00:22:47.334 --> 00:22:50.100
AND SO I TALKED WITH HIM
ABOUT THE POSSIBILITY

00:22:50.100 --> 00:22:52.868
OF COMING THERE
AND WORKING WITH HIM.

00:22:52.868 --> 00:22:56.334
AND HE SAID, "WELL,
THAT'S REALLY GOOD EXCEPT,

00:22:56.334 --> 00:22:57.767
"YOU KNOW,
YOU'RE IN THE BUSINESS

00:22:57.767 --> 00:22:59.100
"OF TELLING PEOPLE STUFF,

00:22:59.100 --> 00:23:01.901
AND WE'RE IN THE BUSINESS
OF KEEPING SECRETS."

00:23:01.901 --> 00:23:03.467
ALL RIGHT, AND THEN
WHAT MADE JON SNODDY

00:23:03.467 --> 00:23:06.167
JON SNODDY WAS HE SAID,
"BUT WE'LL WORK IT OUT,"

00:23:06.167 --> 00:23:07.467
WHICH I REALLY LOVED.

00:23:07.467 --> 00:23:09.300
THE OTHER THING THAT I LEARNED
FROM JON SNODDY--

00:23:09.300 --> 00:23:10.701
I COULD DO EASILY
AN HOUR-LONG TALK

00:23:10.701 --> 00:23:12.400
JUST ON WHAT HAVE I LEARNED
FROM JON SNODDY.

00:23:12.400 --> 00:23:14.200
ONE OF THE THINGS HE TOLD ME
WAS THAT,

00:23:14.200 --> 00:23:17.033
"WAIT LONG ENOUGH, AND PEOPLE
WILL SURPRISE AND IMPRESS YOU."

00:23:17.033 --> 00:23:18.767
HE SAID, "WHEN YOU'RE PISSED OFF
AT SOMEBODY

00:23:18.767 --> 00:23:20.000
"AND YOU'RE ANGRY AT THEM,

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:22.534
"YOU JUST HAVEN'T GIVEN THEM
ENOUGH TIME.

00:23:22.534 --> 00:23:23.934
"JUST GIVE THEM
A LITTLE MORE TIME,

00:23:23.934 --> 00:23:25.501
AND THEY'LL ALMOST ALWAYS
IMPRESS YOU."

00:23:25.501 --> 00:23:26.868
AND THAT REALLY STUCK WITH ME.

00:23:26.868 --> 00:23:28.868
I THINK HE'S ABSOLUTELY RIGHT
ON THAT ONE.

00:23:28.868 --> 00:23:34.567
SO TO MAKE A LONG STORY SHORT,
WE NEGOTIATED A LEGAL CONTRACT.

00:23:34.567 --> 00:23:35.968
IT WAS GOING TO BE THE FIRST--

00:23:35.968 --> 00:23:38.167
SOME PEOPLE REFERRED TO IT
AS THE FIRST AND LAST PAPER

00:23:38.167 --> 00:23:39.968
EVER PUBLISHED BY IMAGINEERING--

00:23:39.968 --> 00:23:42.901
BUT THE DEAL WAS I GO,
I PROVIDE MY OWN FUNDING,

00:23:42.901 --> 00:23:44.667
I GO FOR SIX MONTHS,
I WORK WITH A PROJECT,

00:23:44.667 --> 00:23:47.667
WE PUBLISH A PAPER.

00:23:47.667 --> 00:23:49.601
AND THEN WE MEET OUR VILLAIN.

00:23:51.901 --> 00:23:53.334
I CAN'T BE ALL SWEETNESS
AND LIGHT,

00:23:53.334 --> 00:23:54.868
BECAUSE I HAVE NO CREDIBILITY.

00:23:54.868 --> 00:23:57.234
SOMEBODY'S HEAD'S GOING TO GO
ON A STICK.

00:23:57.234 --> 00:23:59.367
TURNS OUT THAT THE PERSON
WHO GETS HIS HEAD ON THE STICK

00:23:59.367 --> 00:24:01.601
IS A DEAN BACK
AT THE UNIVERSITY OF VIRGINIA.

00:24:01.601 --> 00:24:02.667
HIS NAME IS NOT IMPORTANT.

00:24:02.667 --> 00:24:04.467
LET'S CALL HIM DEAN WORMER.

00:24:04.467 --> 00:24:07.400
[laughter]

00:24:09.934 --> 00:24:12.534
AND DEAN WORMER HAS A MEETING
WITH ME WHERE I SAY,

00:24:12.534 --> 00:24:14.033
"I WANT TO DO
THIS SABBATICAL THING,

00:24:14.033 --> 00:24:15.968
"AND I'VE ACTUALLY GOTTEN
THE IMAGINEERING GUYS

00:24:15.968 --> 00:24:17.667
TO LET AN ACADEMIC IN,"
WHICH IS INSANE.

00:24:17.667 --> 00:24:19.267
I MEAN, IF JON HADN'T GONE NUTS,

00:24:19.267 --> 00:24:20.934
THIS WOULD NEVER HAVE BEEN
A POSSIBILITY.

00:24:20.934 --> 00:24:22.501
THIS IS A VERY
SECRETIVE ORGANIZATION.

00:24:22.501 --> 00:24:23.801
AND DEAN WORMER LOOKS
AT THE PAPERWORK, AND HE SAYS,

00:24:23.801 --> 00:24:25.200
"WELL, IT SAYS
THEY'RE GOING TO OWN

00:24:25.200 --> 00:24:26.634
YOUR INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY."

00:24:26.634 --> 00:24:28.934
AND I SAID, "YEAH, WE GOT THE
AGREEMENT TO PUBLISH THE PAPER.

00:24:28.934 --> 00:24:30.968
"THERE IS NO OTHER IP.
I DON'T DO PATENTABLE STUFF."

00:24:30.968 --> 00:24:32.968
AND HE SAYS, "YEAH,
BUT YOU MIGHT, SO DEAL'S OFF.

00:24:32.968 --> 00:24:36.234
"JUST GO AND GET THEM TO CHANGE
THAT LITTLE CLAUSE THERE

00:24:36.234 --> 00:24:39.501
AND THEN COME BACK TO ME."

00:24:39.501 --> 00:24:41.634
I'M LIKE, "EXCUSE ME?"

00:24:41.634 --> 00:24:43.100
AND THEN I SAID TO HIM,

00:24:43.100 --> 00:24:45.033
"I WANT YOU TO UNDERSTAND
HOW IMPORTANT THIS IS.

00:24:45.033 --> 00:24:46.367
"IF WE CAN'T WORK THIS OUT,

00:24:46.367 --> 00:24:48.767
"I'M GOING TO TAKE
AN UNPAID LEAVE OF ABSENCE,

00:24:48.767 --> 00:24:53.400
AND I'M JUST GOING TO GO THERE,
AND I'M GOING TO DO THIS THING."

00:24:53.400 --> 00:24:55.901
AND HE SAID, "HEY, YOU KNOW,

00:24:55.901 --> 00:24:57.434
"I MIGHT NOT EVEN
LET YOU DO THAT.

00:24:57.434 --> 00:24:59.267
"I MEAN, YOU'VE GOT THE IP
IN YOUR HEAD ALREADY,

00:24:59.267 --> 00:25:01.167
"AND MAYBE THEY'RE GOING
TO SUCK IT OUT OF YOU,

00:25:01.167 --> 00:25:03.601
SO THAT'S NOT GOING
TO FLY EITHER."

00:25:03.601 --> 00:25:06.534
[laughter]

00:25:08.234 --> 00:25:12.367
IT'S VERY IMPORTANT TO KNOW
WHEN YOU'RE IN A PISSING MATCH,

00:25:12.367 --> 00:25:13.467
AND IT'S VERY IMPORTANT

00:25:13.467 --> 00:25:15.934
TO GET OUT OF IT
AS QUICKLY AS POSSIBLE.

00:25:15.934 --> 00:25:19.501
SO I SAID TO HIM, "WELL,
LET'S BACK OFF ON THIS.

00:25:19.501 --> 00:25:21.767
DO WE THINK THIS IS
A GOOD IDEA AT ALL?"

00:25:21.767 --> 00:25:24.601
HE SAID, "I HAVE NO IDEA IF THIS
IS A GOOD IDEA, YOU KNOW."

00:25:24.601 --> 00:25:28.133
I WAS LIKE, "OKAY, WELL,
WE'VE GOT COMMON GROUND THERE."

00:25:28.133 --> 00:25:29.934
THEN I SAID, "WELL,
IS THIS REALLY YOUR CALL?

00:25:29.934 --> 00:25:32.300
ISN'T THIS THE CALL OF
THE DEAN OF SPONSORED RESEARCH

00:25:32.300 --> 00:25:33.367
IF IT'S AN IP ISSUE?"

00:25:33.367 --> 00:25:34.734
AND HE SAID,
"YEAH, THAT'S TRUE."

00:25:34.734 --> 00:25:36.434
I SAID, "BUT SO IF HE'S HAPPY,
YOU'RE HAPPY?"

00:25:36.434 --> 00:25:37.434
"YEAH, THEN I'D BE FINE."

00:25:37.434 --> 00:25:38.434
pew!

00:25:38.434 --> 00:25:39.634
LIKE WILE E. COYOTE.

00:25:39.634 --> 00:25:41.234
AND I FIND MYSELF
IN GENE BLOCK'S OFFICE,

00:25:41.234 --> 00:25:42.901
WHO IS THE MOST FANTASTIC MAN
IN THE WORLD,

00:25:42.901 --> 00:25:44.601
AND I START TALKING
TO GENE BLOCK, AND I SAY,

00:25:44.601 --> 00:25:45.868
"LET'S START AT THE HIGH LEVEL,"

00:25:45.868 --> 00:25:47.000
SINCE I DON'T WANT TO HAVE
TO BACK OUT AGAIN.

00:25:47.000 --> 00:25:48.334
"SO LET'S START
AT THE HIGH LEVEL.

00:25:48.334 --> 00:25:49.801
DO YOU THINK THIS IS
A GOOD IDEA?"

00:25:49.801 --> 00:25:51.868
HE SAID, "WELL, IF YOU'RE ASKING
ME IF IT'S A GOOD IDEA,

00:25:51.868 --> 00:25:53.334
"I DON'T HAVE
VERY MUCH INFORMATION.

00:25:53.334 --> 00:25:55.234
"ALL I KNOW IS THAT ONE
OF MY STAR FACULTY MEMBERS

00:25:55.234 --> 00:25:56.501
"IS IN MY OFFICE,
AND HE'S REALLY EXCITED,

00:25:56.501 --> 00:25:57.834
SO TELL ME MORE."

00:25:57.834 --> 00:25:59.901
HERE'S A LESSON FOR EVERYBODY
IN ADMINISTRATION.

00:25:59.901 --> 00:26:03.100
THEY BOTH SAID THE SAME THING,

00:26:03.100 --> 00:26:07.000
BUT THINK ABOUT
HOW THEY SAID IT, RIGHT?

00:26:07.000 --> 00:26:08.534
"I DON'T KNOW!"

00:26:08.534 --> 00:26:10.100
"WELL, I DON'T HAVE
MUCH INFORMATION,

00:26:10.100 --> 00:26:12.067
"BUT ONE OF MY STAR
FACULTY MEMBERS IS HERE,

00:26:12.067 --> 00:26:14.133
AND HE'S ALL EXCITED,
SO I WANT TO LEARN MORE."

00:26:14.133 --> 00:26:15.868
THEY'RE BOTH WAYS OF SAYING
I DON'T KNOW,

00:26:15.868 --> 00:26:18.067
BUT, BOY, THERE'S A GOOD WAY
AND A BAD WAY.

00:26:18.067 --> 00:26:21.000
SO ANYWAY, WE GOT IT
ALL WORKED OUT.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.901
I WENT TO IMAGINEERING,
SWEETNESS AND LIGHT,

00:26:23.901 --> 00:26:25.501
AND ALL'S WELL THAT ENDS WELL.

00:26:29.434 --> 00:26:33.300
SOME BRICK WALLS
ARE MADE OF FLESH.

00:26:33.300 --> 00:26:35.400
SO I WORKED ON
THE ALADDIN PROJECT.

00:26:35.400 --> 00:26:40.567
IT WAS ABSOLUTELY SPECTACULAR,
I MEAN, JUST UNBELIEVABLE.

00:26:40.567 --> 00:26:41.868
HERE'S MY NEPHEW CHRISTOPHER.

00:26:41.868 --> 00:26:43.200
THIS WAS THE APPARATUS.

00:26:43.200 --> 00:26:45.267
YOU WOULD SIT ON THIS SORT
OF MOTORCYCLE-TYPE THING,

00:26:45.267 --> 00:26:47.501
AND YOU WOULD STEER
YOUR MAGIC CARPET,

00:26:47.501 --> 00:26:49.567
AND YOU WOULD PUT ON
THE HEAD-MOUNTED DISPLAY.

00:26:49.567 --> 00:26:51.501
THE HEAD-MOUNTED DISPLAY
WAS VERY INTERESTING.

00:26:51.501 --> 00:26:53.834
IT HAD TWO PARTS, AND IT WAS
A VERY, VERY CLEVER DESIGN.

00:26:53.834 --> 00:26:55.467
TO GET THROUGHPUT THROUGH,
THE ONLY PART

00:26:55.467 --> 00:26:57.467
THAT TOUCHED THE GUEST'S HEAD
WAS THIS LITTLE CAP,

00:26:57.467 --> 00:26:58.934
AND EVERYTHING ELSE
CLICKED ONTO IT,

00:26:58.934 --> 00:27:00.100
ALL THE EXPENSIVE HARDWARE.

00:27:00.100 --> 00:27:01.467
SO YOU COULD REPLICATE THE CAPS

00:27:01.467 --> 00:27:03.801
BECAUSE THEY WERE BASICALLY
FREE TO MANUFACTURE.

00:27:03.801 --> 00:27:05.133
THIS IS WHAT I REALLY DID IS,

00:27:05.133 --> 00:27:08.934
I WAS A CAP CLEANER
DURING THE SABBATICAL.

00:27:08.934 --> 00:27:11.501
I LOVED IMAGINEERING.

00:27:11.501 --> 00:27:15.334
IT WAS JUST A SPECTACULAR PLACE,
JUST SPECTACULAR,

00:27:15.334 --> 00:27:16.667
EVERYTHING THAT I HAD DREAMED.

00:27:16.667 --> 00:27:18.000
I LOVED THE MODEL SHOP,

00:27:18.000 --> 00:27:20.601
PEOPLE CRAWLING AROUND ON THINGS
THE SIZE OF THIS ROOM

00:27:20.601 --> 00:27:22.067
THAT ARE JUST
BIG PHYSICAL MODELS.

00:27:22.067 --> 00:27:24.767
IT WAS JUST AN INCREDIBLE PLACE
TO WALK AROUND

00:27:24.767 --> 00:27:26.367
AND BE INSPIRED.

00:27:26.367 --> 00:27:29.534
I'M ALWAYS REMINDED OF WHEN
I WENT THERE AND PEOPLE SAID,

00:27:29.534 --> 00:27:31.300
"DO YOU THINK THE EXPECTATIONS
ARE TOO HIGH?"

00:27:31.300 --> 00:27:32.667
AND I SAID, "YOU EVER SEE
THE MOVIE

00:27:32.667 --> 00:27:34.200
"CHARLIE
AND THE CHOCOLATE FACTORY"--

00:27:34.200 --> 00:27:35.801
"WILLY WONKA
AND THE CHOCOLATE FACTORY"

00:27:35.801 --> 00:27:37.367
WHERE GENE WILDER SAYS
TO THE LITTLE BOY CHARLIE--

00:27:37.367 --> 00:27:38.767
HE'S ABOUT TO GIVE HIM
THE CHOCOLATE FACTORY.

00:27:38.767 --> 00:27:40.767
HE SAYS, "WELL, CHARLIE,
DID ANYBODY EVER TELL YOU

00:27:40.767 --> 00:27:42.067
"THE STORY OF THE LITTLE BOY

00:27:42.067 --> 00:27:45.667
WHO SUDDENLY GOT EVERYTHING
HE EVER WANTED?"

00:27:45.667 --> 00:27:48.200
CHARLIE'S EYES GET LIKE SAUCERS,
AND HE SAYS,

00:27:48.200 --> 00:27:50.133
"NO, WHAT HAPPENED TO HIM?"

00:27:50.133 --> 00:27:54.367
GENE WILDER SAYS,
"HE LIVED HAPPILY EVER AFTER."

00:27:54.367 --> 00:27:56.767
OKAY, SO WORKING ON
THE ALADDIN VR,

00:27:56.767 --> 00:27:57.968
I DESCRIBED IT AS

00:27:57.968 --> 00:27:59.734
A ONCE-IN-EVERY-FIVE-YEARS
OPPORTUNITY,

00:27:59.734 --> 00:28:01.300
AND I STAND BY THAT ASSESSMENT.

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:03.234
IT FOREVER CHANGED ME.

00:28:03.234 --> 00:28:04.834
IT WASN'T JUST THAT IT
WAS GOOD WORK

00:28:04.834 --> 00:28:06.968
AND I GOT TO BE A PART OF IT,

00:28:06.968 --> 00:28:10.067
BUT IT GOT ME INTO THE PLACE
OF WORKING WITH REAL PEOPLE

00:28:10.067 --> 00:28:12.601
AND REAL HCI
USER INTERFACE ISSUES.

00:28:12.601 --> 00:28:15.067
MOST HCI PEOPLE LIVE IN THIS
FANTASY WORLD

00:28:15.067 --> 00:28:18.701
OF WHITE COLLAR LABORERS
WITH PhDs AND MASTER'S DEGREES.

00:28:18.701 --> 00:28:20.667
YOU KNOW, UNTIL YOU GOT
ICE CREAM SPILLED ON YOU,

00:28:20.667 --> 00:28:23.901
YOU'RE NOT DOING FIELD WORK,
ALL RIGHT?

00:28:23.901 --> 00:28:26.334
AND MORE THAN ANYTHING ELSE,
FROM JON SNODDY I LEARNED

00:28:26.334 --> 00:28:28.467
HOW TO PUT ARTISTS
AND ENGINEERS TOGETHER,

00:28:28.467 --> 00:28:30.400
AND THAT'S BEEN THE REAL LEGACY.

00:28:30.400 --> 00:28:31.601
WE PUBLISHED A PAPER,

00:28:31.601 --> 00:28:33.434
JUST A NICE ACADEMIC
CULTURAL SCANDAL.

00:28:33.434 --> 00:28:35.601
WHEN WE WROTE THE PAPER,
THE GUYS AT IMAGINEERING SAID,

00:28:35.601 --> 00:28:38.234
"WELL, LET'S DO
A NICE BIG PICTURE

00:28:38.234 --> 00:28:39.968
LIKE YOU WOULD IN A MAGAZINE."

00:28:39.968 --> 00:28:42.067
AND THE SIGGRAPH COMMITTEE,
WHICH ACCEPTED THE PAPER,

00:28:42.067 --> 00:28:43.601
IT WAS LIKE THIS BIG SCANDAL.

00:28:43.601 --> 00:28:45.467
"ARE THEY ALLOWED TO DO THAT?"

00:28:45.467 --> 00:28:47.601
[laughter]

00:28:47.601 --> 00:28:50.467
THERE WAS NO RULE.

00:28:50.467 --> 00:28:52.467
SO WE PUBLISHED THE PAPER,
AND AMAZINGLY,

00:28:52.467 --> 00:28:54.467
SINCE THEN, THERE'S A TRADITION
OF SIGGRAPH PAPERS

00:28:54.467 --> 00:28:57.067
HAVING COLOR FIGURES
ON THE FIRST PAGE.

00:28:57.067 --> 00:29:00.767
SO I'VE CHANGED THE WORLD
IN A SMALL WAY.

00:29:00.767 --> 00:29:04.033
AND THEN AT THE END
OF MY SIX MONTHS,

00:29:04.033 --> 00:29:05.334
THEY CAME TO ME,
AND THEY SAID,

00:29:05.334 --> 00:29:08.767
"YOU WANT TO DO IT FOR REAL?
YOU CAN STAY."

00:29:14.567 --> 00:29:16.567
AND I SAID, "NO."

00:29:16.567 --> 00:29:19.000
ONE OF THE ONLY TIMES IN MY LIFE
I HAVE SURPRISED MY FATHER.

00:29:19.000 --> 00:29:22.033
HE WAS LIKE, "YOU WHAT?"

00:29:22.033 --> 00:29:24.701
HE SAID, "SINCE YOU WERE,
YOU KNOW, ALL YOU WANTED,

00:29:24.701 --> 00:29:27.667
AND NOW THAT YOU GOT IT,
AND YOU'RE--HUH?"

00:29:27.667 --> 00:29:29.634
THERE WAS A BOTTLE OF MAALOX
IN MY DESK DRAWER.

00:29:29.634 --> 00:29:30.834
BE CAREFUL WHAT YOU WISH FOR.

00:29:30.834 --> 00:29:32.534
IT WAS A PARTICULARLY
STRESSFUL PLACE.

00:29:32.534 --> 00:29:35.534
IMAGINEERING IN GENERAL
IS ACTUALLY NOT SO MAALOX-LADEN,

00:29:35.534 --> 00:29:39.067
BUT THE LAB I WAS IN--
OH, JON LEFT IN THE MIDDLE,

00:29:39.067 --> 00:29:41.667
AND IT WAS A LOT LIKE
THE SOVIET UNION.

00:29:41.667 --> 00:29:44.133
IT WAS A LITTLE DICEY
FOR A WHILE,

00:29:44.133 --> 00:29:45.501
BUT IT WORKED OUT OKAY,

00:29:45.501 --> 00:29:47.601
AND IF THEY HAD SAID,
"STAY HERE

00:29:47.601 --> 00:29:49.067
OR NEVER WALK
IN THE BUILDING AGAIN,"

00:29:49.067 --> 00:29:50.734
I WOULD HAVE DONE IT.

00:29:50.734 --> 00:29:52.467
I WOULD HAVE WALKED AWAY
FROM TENURE.

00:29:52.467 --> 00:29:54.100
I WOULD HAVE JUST DONE IT.

00:29:54.100 --> 00:29:55.334
BUT THEY MADE IT EASY ON ME.

00:29:55.334 --> 00:29:57.267
THEY SAID, "YOU CAN HAVE
YOUR CAKE AND EAT IT TOO,"

00:29:57.267 --> 00:29:58.367
AND I BASICALLY BECOME

00:29:58.367 --> 00:30:00.133
A DAY-A-WEEK CONSULTANT
FOR IMAGINEERING,

00:30:00.133 --> 00:30:01.634
AND I DID THAT
FOR ABOUT TEN YEARS,

00:30:01.634 --> 00:30:03.100
AND THAT'S ONE OF THE REASONS

00:30:03.100 --> 00:30:05.701
YOU SHOULD ALL
BECOME PROFESSORS,

00:30:05.701 --> 00:30:09.767
BECAUSE YOU CAN HAVE YOUR CAKE
AND EAT IT TOO, OKAY?

00:30:09.767 --> 00:30:11.968
I WENT ON AND CONSULTED
ON THINGS LIKE DISNEYQUEST.

00:30:11.968 --> 00:30:13.801
SO THERE WAS
THE VIRTUAL JUNGLE CRUISE

00:30:13.801 --> 00:30:16.834
AND THE BEST INTERACTIVE
EXPERIENCE I THINK EVER DONE--

00:30:16.834 --> 00:30:18.968
AND JESSE SCHELL
GETS THE CREDIT FOR THIS--

00:30:18.968 --> 00:30:23.067
PIRATES OF THE CARIBBEAN,
WONDERFUL AT DISNEYQUEST.

00:30:23.067 --> 00:30:24.868
AND SO THOSE ARE
MY CHILDHOOD DREAMS,

00:30:24.868 --> 00:30:27.000
AND, YOU KNOW,
THAT'S PRETTY GOOD.

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:28.267
I FELT GOOD ABOUT THAT.

00:30:28.267 --> 00:30:29.968
SO THEN THE QUESTION BECOMES,

00:30:29.968 --> 00:30:33.033
HOW CAN I ENABLE
THE CHILDHOOD DREAMS OF OTHERS?

00:30:33.033 --> 00:30:35.868
AND AGAIN, BOY, AM I GLAD
I BECAME A PROFESSOR.

00:30:35.868 --> 00:30:41.868
WHAT BETTER PLACE
TO ENABLE CHILDHOOD DREAMS?

00:30:41.868 --> 00:30:43.234
MAYBE WORKING AT EA,
I DON'T KNOW.

00:30:43.234 --> 00:30:47.467
THAT'D PROBABLY BE
A GOOD CLOSE SECOND.

00:30:47.467 --> 00:30:52.601
AND THIS STARTED IN
A VERY CONCRETE REALIZATION

00:30:52.601 --> 00:30:54.400
THAT I COULD DO THIS,

00:30:54.400 --> 00:30:56.167
BECAUSE A YOUNG MAN
NAMED TOMMY BURNETTE,

00:30:56.167 --> 00:30:58.200
WHEN I WAS AT THE UNIVERSITY
OF VIRGINIA, CAME TO ME,

00:30:58.200 --> 00:31:00.300
WAS INTERESTED IN JOINING
MY RESEARCH GROUP,

00:31:00.300 --> 00:31:02.300
AND WE TALKED ABOUT IT,
AND HE SAID,

00:31:02.300 --> 00:31:04.534
"OH, AND I HAVE
A CHILDHOOD DREAM."

00:31:04.534 --> 00:31:07.701
IT GETS PRETTY EASY TO RECOGNIZE
THEM WHEN THEY TELL YOU.

00:31:07.701 --> 00:31:10.133
AND I SAID, "YES, TOMMY,
WHAT IS YOUR CHILDHOOD DREAM?"

00:31:10.133 --> 00:31:14.834
HE SAID, "I WANT TO WORK ON
THE NEXT "STAR WARS" FILM."

00:31:14.834 --> 00:31:16.934
NOW, YOU GOT TO REMEMBER
THE TIMING ON THIS.

00:31:16.934 --> 00:31:18.400
WHERE IS TOMMY?
TOMMY IS HERE TODAY.

00:31:18.400 --> 00:31:20.734
WHAT YEAR WOULD THIS HAVE BEEN?
YOUR SOPHOMORE YEAR.

00:31:20.734 --> 00:31:21.734
woman: RIGHT THERE.

00:31:21.734 --> 00:31:23.133
man: IT WAS AROUND 1993.

00:31:23.133 --> 00:31:25.434
Pausch: ARE YOU BREAKING
ANYTHING BACK THERE, YOUNG MAN?

00:31:25.434 --> 00:31:27.400
OKAY, ALL RIGHT, SO IN 1993.

00:31:27.400 --> 00:31:29.601
AND I SAID TO TOMMY,
"YOU KNOW

00:31:29.601 --> 00:31:33.067
THEY'RE PROBABLY NOT GOING
TO MAKE THOSE NEXT MOVIES."

00:31:33.067 --> 00:31:36.000
[laughter]

00:31:38.033 --> 00:31:41.667
AND HE SAID, "NO, THEY ARE."

00:31:41.667 --> 00:31:44.601
[laughter]

00:31:45.868 --> 00:31:48.934
AND TOMMY WORKED WITH ME
FOR A NUMBER OF YEARS

00:31:48.934 --> 00:31:50.767
AS AN UNDERGRADUATE
AND THEN AS A STAFF MEMBER,

00:31:50.767 --> 00:31:52.534
AND THEN WHEN I MOVED
TO CARNEGIE MELLON,

00:31:52.534 --> 00:31:54.534
EVERY SINGLE MEMBER OF MY TEAM

00:31:54.534 --> 00:31:57.267
CAME FROM VIRGINIA
TO CARNEGIE MELLON

00:31:57.267 --> 00:32:00.901
EXCEPT FOR TOMMY,
BECAUSE HE GOT A BETTER OFFER,

00:32:00.901 --> 00:32:03.534
AND HE DID, INDEED,
WORK ON ALL

00:32:03.534 --> 00:32:07.100
THREE OF THOSE FILMS.

00:32:07.100 --> 00:32:08.534
AND THEN I SAID,
"WELL, THAT'S NICE,

00:32:08.534 --> 00:32:11.667
BUT, YOU KNOW, ONE AT A TIME
IS KIND OF INEFFICIENT."

00:32:11.667 --> 00:32:14.334
AND PEOPLE WHO KNOW ME KNOW
THAT I'M AN EFFICIENCY FREAK.

00:32:14.334 --> 00:32:16.534
SO I SAID, "CAN I DO THIS
EN MASSE?

00:32:16.534 --> 00:32:19.200
CAN I GET PEOPLE TURNED
IN SUCH A WAY

00:32:19.200 --> 00:32:21.734
THAT THEY CAN BE TURNED ON
TO THEIR CHILDHOOD DREAMS?"

00:32:21.734 --> 00:32:23.667
AND I CREATED A COURSE,
I CAME TO CARNEGIE MELLON,

00:32:23.667 --> 00:32:25.868
AND I CREATED A COURSE CALLED
"BUILDING VIRTUAL WORLDS."

00:32:25.868 --> 00:32:27.300
IT'S A VERY SIMPLE COURSE.

00:32:27.300 --> 00:32:30.267
HOW MANY PEOPLE HERE HAVE
EVER BEEN TO ANY OF THE SHOWS?

00:32:30.267 --> 00:32:31.734
OKAY, SO SOME OF YOU HAVE
AN IDEA.

00:32:31.734 --> 00:32:33.801
FOR THOSE OF YOU WHO DON'T,
THE COURSE IS VERY SIMPLE.

00:32:33.801 --> 00:32:35.133
THERE ARE 50 STUDENTS DRAWN

00:32:35.133 --> 00:32:37.467
FROM ALL THE DIFFERENT
DEPARTMENTS OF THE UNIVERSITY.

00:32:37.467 --> 00:32:39.834
THERE ARE RANDOMLY CHOSEN--

00:32:39.834 --> 00:32:43.200
RANDOMLY CHOSEN TEAMS,
FOUR PEOPLE PER TEAM,

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:44.767
AND THEY CHANGE EVERY PROJECT.

00:32:44.767 --> 00:32:47.434
A PROJECT ONLY LASTS TWO WEEKS,
SO YOU DO SOMETHING,

00:32:47.434 --> 00:32:49.634
YOU MAKE SOMETHING,
YOU SHOW SOMETHING,

00:32:49.634 --> 00:32:52.067
THEN I SHUFFLE THE TEAMS,
YOU GET THREE NEW PLAYMATES,

00:32:52.067 --> 00:32:55.467
AND YOU DO IT AGAIN,
AND IT'S EVERY TWO WEEKS,

00:32:55.467 --> 00:32:58.834
AND SO YOU DO FIVE PROJECTS
DURING THE SEMESTER.

00:32:58.834 --> 00:33:00.601
THE FIRST YEAR
WE TAUGHT THIS COURSE,

00:33:00.601 --> 00:33:03.000
IT IS IMPOSSIBLE TO DESCRIBE

00:33:03.000 --> 00:33:06.133
HOW MUCH OF A TIGER BY THE TAIL
WE HAD.

00:33:06.133 --> 00:33:07.400
I WAS JUST RUNNING THE COURSE

00:33:07.400 --> 00:33:09.167
BECAUSE I WANTED TO SEE
IF WE COULD DO IT.

00:33:09.167 --> 00:33:11.601
WE HAD JUST LEARNED HOW TO DO
TEXTURE MAPPING ON 3D GRAPHICS,

00:33:11.601 --> 00:33:13.501
AND WE COULD MAKE STUFF
THAT LOOKED HALF DECENT.

00:33:13.501 --> 00:33:14.734
BUT, YOU KNOW, WE WERE RUNNING

00:33:14.734 --> 00:33:17.934
ON REALLY WEAK COMPUTERS
BY CURRENT STANDARDS.

00:33:17.934 --> 00:33:19.300
BUT I SAID, "I'LL GIVE IT
A TRY."

00:33:19.300 --> 00:33:21.467
AND AT MY NEW UNIVERSITY,
I MADE A COUPLE OF PHONE CALLS,

00:33:21.467 --> 00:33:23.234
AND I SAID, "I WANT
TO CROSS-LIST THIS COURSE

00:33:23.234 --> 00:33:25.234
TO GET ALL THESE OTHER PEOPLE,"
AND WITHIN 24 HOURS,

00:33:25.234 --> 00:33:27.901
IT WAS CROSS-LISTED
IN FIVE DEPARTMENTS.

00:33:27.901 --> 00:33:29.501
I LOVE THIS UNIVERSITY.

00:33:29.501 --> 00:33:32.067
I MEAN, IT'S JUST--
IT'S THE MOST AMAZING PLACE.

00:33:32.067 --> 00:33:34.100
AND THE KIDS SAID, "WELL,
WHAT CONTENT DO WE MAKE?"

00:33:34.100 --> 00:33:36.000
I SAID, "HELL, I DON'T KNOW.

00:33:36.000 --> 00:33:37.334
"YOU MAKE WHATEVER YOU WANT.

00:33:37.334 --> 00:33:41.367
TWO RULES: NO SHOOTING VIOLENCE
AND NO PORNOGRAPHY."

00:33:41.367 --> 00:33:43.868
NOT BECAUSE I'M OPPOSED TO THOSE
IN PARTICULAR,

00:33:43.868 --> 00:33:48.968
BUT, YOU KNOW, THAT'S BEEN DONE
WITH VR, RIGHT?

00:33:48.968 --> 00:33:50.968
AND YOU'D BE AMAZED
HOW MANY 19-YEAR-OLD BOYS

00:33:50.968 --> 00:33:54.534
ARE COMPLETELY OUT OF IDEAS WHEN
YOU TAKE THOSE OFF THE TABLE.

00:33:54.534 --> 00:33:57.467
[laughter]

00:33:59.667 --> 00:34:01.934
ANYWAY, SO I TAUGHT THE COURSE.

00:34:01.934 --> 00:34:04.200
THE FIRST ASSIGNMENT,
I GAVE IT TO THEM,

00:34:04.200 --> 00:34:08.200
THEY CAME BACK IN TWO WEEKS,
AND THEY JUST BLEW ME AWAY.

00:34:08.200 --> 00:34:12.067
I MEAN, THE WORK WAS SO BEYOND,
LITERALLY, MY IMAGINATION,

00:34:12.067 --> 00:34:14.734
BECAUSE I HAD COPIED THE PROCESS
FROM IMAGINEERING'S VR LAB,

00:34:14.734 --> 00:34:16.234
BUT I HAD NO IDEA

00:34:16.234 --> 00:34:19.367
WHAT THEY COULD OR COULDN'T DO
WITH IT AS UNDERGRADUATES,

00:34:19.367 --> 00:34:20.601
AND THEIR TOOLS WERE WEAKER,

00:34:20.601 --> 00:34:22.300
AND THEY CAME BACK
ON THE FIRST ASSIGNMENT,

00:34:22.300 --> 00:34:24.167
AND THEY DID SOMETHING
THAT WAS SO SPECTACULAR

00:34:24.167 --> 00:34:26.300
THAT I LITERALLY DIDN'T--
TEN YEARS AS A PROFESSOR,

00:34:26.300 --> 00:34:28.067
AND I HAD NO IDEA
WHAT TO DO NEXT.

00:34:28.067 --> 00:34:29.801
SO I CALLED UP MY MENTOR.

00:34:29.801 --> 00:34:33.300
I CALLED UP ANDY VAN DAM,
AND I SAID,

00:34:33.300 --> 00:34:35.133
"ANDY, I JUST GAVE
A TWO-WEEK ASSIGNMENT,

00:34:35.133 --> 00:34:36.467
"AND THEY CAME BACK
AND DID STUFF

00:34:36.467 --> 00:34:38.133
"THAT IF I HAD GIVEN THEM
A WHOLE SEMESTER,

00:34:38.133 --> 00:34:39.601
"I WOULD HAVE GIVEN THEM
ALL "A"s.

00:34:39.601 --> 00:34:43.701
SENSEI, WHAT DO I DO?"

00:34:43.701 --> 00:34:47.601
AND ANDY THOUGHT FOR A MINUTE,
AND HE SAID,

00:34:47.601 --> 00:34:49.667
"YOU GO BACK
INTO CLASS TOMORROW,

00:34:49.667 --> 00:34:51.567
"AND YOU LOOK THEM IN THE EYE,
AND YOU SAY,

00:34:51.567 --> 00:34:54.634
'GUYS, THAT WAS PRETTY GOOD,
BUT I KNOW YOU CAN DO BETTER.'"

00:34:54.634 --> 00:34:57.567
[laughter]

00:34:58.734 --> 00:35:00.267
AND THAT WAS EXACTLY
THE RIGHT ADVICE,

00:35:00.267 --> 00:35:01.667
BECAUSE WHAT HE SAID WAS,

00:35:01.667 --> 00:35:05.067
"YOU OBVIOUSLY DON'T KNOW
WHERE THE BAR SHOULD BE,

00:35:05.067 --> 00:35:07.300
"AND YOU'RE ONLY GOING
TO DO THEM A DISSERVICE

00:35:07.300 --> 00:35:10.067
BY PUTTING IT ANYWHERE."

00:35:10.067 --> 00:35:12.200
AND, BOY,
WAS THAT GOOD ADVICE,

00:35:12.200 --> 00:35:16.367
BECAUSE THEY JUST KEPT GOING,
AND DURING THAT SEMESTER,

00:35:16.367 --> 00:35:18.601
IT BECAME
THIS UNDERGROUND THING.

00:35:18.601 --> 00:35:21.467
I'D WALK INTO A CLASS
WITH 50 STUDENTS IN IT,

00:35:21.467 --> 00:35:25.968
AND THERE WERE 95 PEOPLE
IN THE ROOM,

00:35:25.968 --> 00:35:27.934
BECAUSE IT WAS THE DAY
WE WERE SHOWING WORK,

00:35:27.934 --> 00:35:31.601
AND PEOPLE'S ROOMMATES
AND FRIENDS AND PARENTS--

00:35:31.601 --> 00:35:34.901
I'D NEVER HAD PARENTS
COME TO CLASS BEFORE.

00:35:34.901 --> 00:35:37.501
IT WAS FLATTERING
AND SOMEWHAT SCARY.

00:35:37.501 --> 00:35:40.300
AND SO IT SNOWBALLED, AND WE HAD
THIS BIZARRE THING OF,

00:35:40.300 --> 00:35:41.734
"WELL, WE'VE GOT TO SHARE THIS."

00:35:41.734 --> 00:35:43.434
IF THERE'S ANYTHING
I'VE BEEN RAISED TO DO,

00:35:43.434 --> 00:35:44.801
IT'S TO SHARE,
AND I SAID,

00:35:44.801 --> 00:35:46.734
"WE'VE GOT TO SHOW THIS
AT THE END OF THE SEMESTER.

00:35:46.734 --> 00:35:47.834
WE'VE GOT TO HAVE A BIG SHOW."

00:35:47.834 --> 00:35:49.167
AND WE BOOKED THIS ROOM,
MCCONOMY.

00:35:49.167 --> 00:35:50.767
I HAVE A LOT OF GOOD MEMORIES
IN THIS ROOM.

00:35:50.767 --> 00:35:52.934
AND WE BOOKED IT NOT BECAUSE
WE THOUGHT WE COULD FILL IT,

00:35:52.934 --> 00:35:55.734
BUT BECAUSE IT HAD THE ONLY A/V
SETUP THAT WOULD WORK,

00:35:55.734 --> 00:36:00.100
BECAUSE THIS WAS A ZOO,
COMPUTERS AND EVERYTHING.

00:36:00.100 --> 00:36:02.934
AND THEN WE FILLED IT,
AND WE MORE THAN FILLED IT.

00:36:02.934 --> 00:36:04.501
WE HAD PEOPLE STANDING
IN THE AISLE.

00:36:04.501 --> 00:36:07.133
I WILL NEVER FORGET THE DEAN
AT THE TIME, JIM MORRIS,

00:36:07.133 --> 00:36:09.801
WAS SITTING ON THE STAGE
RIGHT ABOUT THERE.

00:36:09.801 --> 00:36:12.968
WE HAD TO KIND OF SCOOT HIM
OUT OF THE WAY.

00:36:12.968 --> 00:36:15.267
AND THE ENERGY IN THE ROOM
WAS LIKE NOTHING

00:36:15.267 --> 00:36:17.534
I HAD EVER EXPERIENCED BEFORE,
AND PRESIDENT COHON,

00:36:17.534 --> 00:36:21.234
JERRY COHON WAS THERE,
AND HE SENSED THE SAME THING.

00:36:21.234 --> 00:36:22.567
HE LATER DESCRIBED IT AS LIKE

00:36:22.567 --> 00:36:27.834
AN OHIO STATE FOOTBALL PEP RALLY
EXCEPT FOR ACADEMICS,

00:36:27.834 --> 00:36:30.033
AND HE CAME OVER, AND HE ASKED
EXACTLY THE RIGHT QUESTION.

00:36:30.033 --> 00:36:31.367
HE SAID, "BEFORE YOU START,"

00:36:31.367 --> 00:36:34.100
HE SAID, "I GOT TO KNOW,
WHERE ARE THESE PEOPLE FROM?"

00:36:34.100 --> 00:36:36.400
HE SAID, "THE AUDIENCE,
WHAT DEPARTMENTS ARE THEY FROM?"

00:36:36.400 --> 00:36:38.701
AND WE POLLED THEM,
AND IT WAS ALL THE DEPARTMENTS,

00:36:38.701 --> 00:36:39.834
AND I FELT VERY GOOD,

00:36:39.834 --> 00:36:41.534
BECAUSE I HAD
JUST COME TO CAMPUS.

00:36:41.534 --> 00:36:43.100
HE HAD JUST COME TO CAMPUS,

00:36:43.100 --> 00:36:46.567
AND MY NEW BOSS HAD SEEN
IN A VERY CORPORAL WAY

00:36:46.567 --> 00:36:50.534
THAT THIS IS THE UNIVERSITY
THAT PUTS EVERYBODY TOGETHER,

00:36:50.534 --> 00:36:53.801
AND THAT MADE ME FEEL
JUST TREMENDOUS.

00:36:53.801 --> 00:36:55.367
SO WE DID
THIS CAMPUS-WIDE EXHIBITION.

00:36:55.367 --> 00:36:56.801
PEOPLE PERFORMED DOWN HERE.

00:36:56.801 --> 00:36:59.367
THEY'RE IN COSTUME,
AND WE PROJECT JUST LIKE THIS,

00:36:59.367 --> 00:37:00.934
AND YOU CAN SEE
WHAT'S GOING ON.

00:37:00.934 --> 00:37:02.400
YOU CAN SEE WHAT THEY'RE SEEING

00:37:02.400 --> 00:37:03.400
IN THE HEAD MOUNT.

00:37:03.400 --> 00:37:04.734
THERE'S A LOT OF BIG PROPS.

00:37:04.734 --> 00:37:08.200
SO THERE'S A GUY
WHITE WATER RAFTING.

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:13.400
THIS IS BEN IN "E.T."

00:37:13.400 --> 00:37:15.100
AND YES, I DID TELL THEM
IF THEY DIDN'T DO

00:37:15.100 --> 00:37:16.834
THE SHOT OF THE KIDS
BIKING ACROSS THE MOON,

00:37:16.834 --> 00:37:17.834
I WOULD FAIL HIM.

00:37:17.834 --> 00:37:19.400
THAT IS A TRUE STORY.

00:37:19.400 --> 00:37:21.501
AND I THOUGHT
I'D SHOW YOU JUST--

00:37:21.501 --> 00:37:25.300
[laughter]

00:37:25.300 --> 00:37:26.868
SO I THOUGHT I'D SHOW YOU
JUST ONE WORLD,

